<FIRST>r w PM-US-Exports     01-14 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Exports,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Verity Says US Products Below World Standards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing Commerce Secretary C. William Verity
says many American products are below world standards of quality and
the Japanese are two years ahead in developing salable products from
American inventions.
   Blaming antitrust laws for a large part of the problem, Verity
urged President-elect Bush to prepare for ``economic warfare'' in
the 1990s.
   ``What's going to be on the top burner of the 1990s for the Bush
administration is trading, and how is America going to make sure it
will be the number one player,'' Verity said Friday in a last speech
for ``Export Now,'' a campaign he has pressed in his 18 months in
office.
   As President Reagan retires next week, Verity will follow. An old
friend of Bush from the Texas oil industry, Robert Mosbacher, has
been named to succeed him.
   ``The reason that many American products are not selling abroad
is very simple: because they don't have sufficient quality to do
it,'' he said.
   He told how his family company, Armco, Inc., had been a big
supplier of sheet steel to the American auto industry, but had to
work five years to produce steel that would meet the standards of
Honda, the Japanese auto-maker.
   Verity says antitrust laws discourage cooperation of American
companies, creating a barrier to more effective competition.
   ``It (should) be possible for high technology companies or other
companies to get together, not only just research together, but
develop and produce together and market together and then compete,''
he said.
   ``That's what has to happen if we're going to stay in some very
important markets including the semiconductor market ... or high
definition television, or super-conductivity, and there's much more
coming down the path.''
   This country has some marvelous technology, but it is less expert
at transforming theoretical discoveries into products that can sell,
he complained.
   ``The Japanese can do this two years quicker than we can,'' he
said.
   ``This is a serious problem if we develop a technology but if the
Japanese take our technology and use it and we're two years delayed
in getting into the marketplace ... That's going to be disastrous to
this country.''
   Verity's criticism of U.S. industry was not the first from a high
figure in the Reagan administration. Richard G. Darman, who was
deputy to former Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, has
criticized what he called a ``corpocracy'' in American business for
what he saw as lack of initiative.
   Baker is to be secretary of State under President Bush, and
Darman will head the Office of Management and Budget.
</TEXT>
