<FIRST>r a AM-People-Sadler 1stLd-Writethru   01-14 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Sadler, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0796,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Green Beret Ballad' Singer Barry Sadler Center Of Guardian Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The 48-year-old...his guardian,' to CORRECT
year Sadler had No. 1 hit to 1966 sted 1965.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Barry Sadler, brain-damaged
from shooting, was ordered Friday to undergo psychiatric evaluation
by a judge who may appoint a guardian for the ``Ballad of the Green
Berets'' singer.
   Judge John Donnelly filed a restraining order preventing Sadler
from being moved against his will from Cleveland, and said Sadler
must be evaluated by Jan. 20 to determine if he is competent to make
his own decisions.
   The judge said he will decide after the evaluation if the court
has jurisdiction to make Sadler's mother his guardian.
   ``If he is competent, maybe we don't need a guardian,'' said
Donnelly, adding that Sadler's 24-year-old son, Thor, would be
allowed to visit his father Friday.
   The 48-year-old author and singer-songwriter, whose ``Ballad of
the Green Berets'' was a No. 1 hit in 1966, is at the center of
competing legal bids from his mother and son to become his guardian.
   A judge in Nashville, Tenn., on Tuesday named Thor as temporary
guardian, but Donnelly said that judge agreed Friday to the
psychiatric evaluation.
   Sadler, who was shot in the head in Guatemala City in September,
checked out of Cleveland's Wade Park Veterans Administration
hospital Sunday against medical advice.
   Sadler left after he learned hospital officials planned to send
him back to a Nashville VA hospital, said his attorney, Joseph
Meissner.
   Thor Sadler said, ``30 percent of his brain was destroyed when
the bullet went through it. ... I don't know if he is capable of
making decisions.''
   Meissner said Friday that Sadler is mentally competent and wants
his mother, Blanche Bebe Sadler, appointed guardian to help him
conduct his affairs.
   A hearing is set in Nashville Wednesday on a petition filed Jan.
10 by Sadler's wife, Lavona Ruth, and children, Thor, Baron and
Brooke, asking the court to appoint one of them guardian and return
Sadler to Nashville.
   Guatemala City police reports indicate Sadler was shot by
accident when a gun fell out of his pocket and went off while he was
riding in a taxi, his son said.
   Sadler also is the author of more than 20 books, featuring Casca,
a mercenary con demned to everlasting life until the Second Coming
of Jesus Christ.
</TEXT>
