<DOCNO> AP890114-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     01-14 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Angela Lansbury has insisted she's
leaving the popular detective program, ``Murder, She Wrote,''
negotiations are under way to keep her in the role of Jessica
Fletcher.
   Universal TV spokesman Bob Crutchfield said Lansbury's contract
would expire soon. ``She only came aboard for five years,'' he said.
   Her one-hour show, which debuted in September 1984, has
frequently been CBS' most popular series.
   Kim LeMasters, president of CBS Entertainment, said Thursday that
``heated'' negotiations were being conducted between Miss Lansbury
and Universal TV, the show's producer.
   Last fall, Miss Lansbury said she wanted to end the series to do
movies and return to Broadway, where she won four Tony awards.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard M. Nixon, who
suffered from the Watergate tapes, is at the center of a more recent
taping incident.
   Orange County Supervisor Gaddi H. Vasquez now admits he recorded
a call from the former president last month.
   In California, taping a telephone conversation without the
consent of both parties is a misdemeanor. Vasquez, a former police
officer, acknowledged taping Nixon after earlier denying it, but
said Thursday that Nixon gave his permission.
   He said Nixon knew he was being taped by the telltale beeps
coming from his machine. ``I considered it a private matter, a
memento for me and my family,'' Vasquez said.
   Nixon aide John Taylor said Vasquez never asked permission, but
Nixon knew he was being taped because of the beeping and didn't
object.
   Nixon called Vasquez to thank him for making a speech at the Dec.
2 groundbreaking for the Nixon Presidential Library in Yorba Linda,
30 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pele, the retired king of Brazilian
soccer, said in an interview published today that he quit a
government public relations job to avoid ``lying'' about his country.
   Pele, who retired as a player in 1977, last year resigned as
goodwill ambassador for the government tourism agency Embratur.
   In an interview with the Rio newspaper Jornal do Brasil, Pele
said he quit because he was embarrassed by questions about violence
and street crime in Brazil. ``I just couldn't go on lying any
more,'' he said.
   Pele, 48, said the last straw came when Embratur asked him to
promote a Brazilian perfume in the United States. ``I was paid to
defend Brazil and not to sell perfume,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Ricky Skaggs leaves
Monday for a 15-day USO tour that will include seven shows for
American military personnel.
   He will be joined by country singer Suzy Bogguss for United
Service Organizations' performances in Okinawa, the Philippines and
at an installation in the Indian Ocean.
   The shows will be taped for a special on The Nashville Network on
cable TV.
   Skaggs' hits include ``Country Boy'' and ``Heartbroke.'' He was
voted entertainer of the year in 1985 by the Country Music
Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The food company owned by actor Paul
Newman will be donating $5 million to charities this year, a
spokesman said.
   Newman's Own Inc. was started in 1982, and after this year's
donations, will have given $20 million to charities, said A.E.
Hotchner, executive vice president and treasurer of the
Westport-based company.
   Charities getting donations include Aging in America, Research to
Prevent Blindness, Students Against Driving Drunk, the Alzheimer's
Disease Association, Save the Children, and United Friends of
Children, he said Friday.
   The company's products include salad dressing, spaghetti sauce,
popcorn and lemonade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dillards, a bluegrass band popular in
the 1960s, have reunited to launch their first tour in 23 years.
   The Dillards gained fame as the musical Darling family on ``The
Andy Griffith Show.'' Their tour began with a concert here Thursday
night.
   The idea for a reunion tour originated last year when Denver
Pyle, who played the Darling family patriarch on the Griffith show,
suggested a Darling family reunion.
   ``We had so much fun we decided to take the opportunity to find
out if we could do it as well as we used to,'' said bassist Mitch
Jayne. ``We're all still alive, and we all like each other, so we're
one of the few bands anywhere that can still get together.''
   Other members of the band are banjo player Doug Dillard,
mandolinist Dean Webb, guitarist and vocalist Rodney Dillard and
newcomer guitarist Steve Cooley.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of wrangling, negotiations over Daniel
Barenboim's contract as artistic and musical director of the new
Opera-Bastille broke off and the job was declared vacant.
   Pierre Berge, chairman of the board of the multimillion-dollar
Opera-Bastille complex currently under construction in Paris, said
Friday he was sorry an agreement could not be reached with
Barenboim, ``a man whose talent I admire and respect.''
   The conflict centered on money and the number of performances by
Barenboim, 46, an Israeli, he said.
   Barenboim said he planned to take legal action. ``In any case I
have not resigned; the contract is not interrupted, it is broken.''
</TEXT>
