<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-USNewsCase     01-14 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US News Case,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Ruling Against US News Retirees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 retirees of U.S. News &amp; World
Report have lost another round in their court claim that they were
underpaid $100 million in profit-sharing benefits.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals on Friday upheld a lower court decision
that said the retirees were paid a fair value for their company
stock before 1982, even though employees who held stock when the
news magazine was sold two years later received much more per share.
   The 230 plaintiffs, who retired between 1974 and 1982, were paid
an average of $100 a share, said their attorney, Alan Raywid. The
magazine's 1984 employees got $2,842 a share when U.S. News was
sold, according to court papers.
   ``We think the opinion is wrong,'' said Raywid, who added there
is a ``substantial likelihood'' it will be appealed. The
three-member court effectively said companies ``can sacrifice the
interests of past employees and retirees'' to benefit current and
future employees and maintain employee ownership, he said.
   Under the U.S. News profit-sharing plan, when an employee retired
the company could exercise its option to buy the employee's stock
shares.
   According to court papers, employees who retired in 1973 received
$65 a share, while the value rose to $470 for those who retired in
1981.
   The magazine was sold for $176 million in 1984 to media and real
estate magnate Mortimer Zuckerman.
   Raywid said the plaintiffs had received a total of $5.5 million
for their stock but believed they would have gotten $100 million
more if they had been given full value.
   The plaintiffs contended the company that appraised the
magazine's value improperly classified retirees' stock as a minority
interest rather than a majority interest, which would have carried a
higher premium.
   In addition, the plaintiffs said the appraiser placed an unfairly
low value on property U.S. News owned in Washington D.C.
   However, the Court of Appeals upheld the decision to give the
retirees' stock a minority status, saying it was ``entirely
consistent'' with the profit-sharing plan's rules and with federal
law.
   The court also affirmed the property valuation, saying much of
the land was being used as a parking lot and development had not
been expected at the time.
   A major objective of the profit-sharing plan was the perpetuation
of employee ownership, the appellate court said, adding that the law
does not set an exclusive goal of maximizing benefits.
   ``The plaintiffs were not the only beneficiaries of the plan,''
the judges said. ``Indeed, the worst that can be said of the plan is
that it was administered to favor a rolling class of future
beneficiaries over those present and past.''
   Ruling in the case were Circuit Judges Harry T. Edwards, James L.
Buckley and Stephen F. Williams.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
