<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-WarOrphans     01-14 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-War Orphans,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government May Postpone `War Orphan' Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan may postpone a visit by 60 Chinese ``war
orphans'' from World War II who are scheduled to arrive the same day
as Emperor Hirohito's funeral, officials said today.
   The Health and Welfare Ministry is concerned that their arrival
on Feb. 24 would focus attention on World War II tragedies while
more than 100 foreign dignitaries take part in a state funeral for
Hirohito, news reports quoted ministry officials as saying.
   Hirohito died of cancer one week ago at age 87.
   The war orphans, the offspring of Japanese nationals who resided
in northern China and Manchuria during Japan's invasion of East
Asia, were left behind as infants in the turmoil following Japan's
defeat in 1945.
   Since 1981, about 18 groups of orphans from China have come to
Japan to search for their Japanese relatives.
   Officials at the National Olympics Memorial Youth Center, where
the orphans would stay, said the government ministry had asked them
if the facility would be available at a later date if the visit,
originally scheduled for Feb. 24-March 10, is postponed.
   Under a 1988 agreement between China and Japan, about 100 orphans
are scheduled to visit this year.
</TEXT>
