<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Wallenberg 1stLd-Writethru   01-14 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Wallenberg, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0451,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Group Asks Soviets To Trace Swedish Diplomat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 7 beginning: In 1944 to add dropped word. Picks up
graf 8 pvs, `An estimated ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian Jewish group has asked the Soviet Union
to set up an international commission to trace a Swedish diplomat
who disappeared in Soviet custody after saving thousands of Jews
from the Holocaust.
   Many believe Raoul Wallenberg, credited with saving 103,000 Jews
in World War II, is still alive in a Soviet prison. If so, he would
be 77.
   ``We're not confident we know everything that could be known,''
David Matas, vice president of B'nai B'rith Canada, told reporters
Friday. ``This would be a true test of the new Soviet policy of
glasnost.''
   When Soviet troops liberated Hungary in January 1945, Wallenberg
was arrested for espionage and sent to Moscow. The Soviets say he
died of a heart attack in a Moscow jail in 1947, but various Soviet
dissident sources have reported seeing him this decade.
   Matas discussed the issue Friday with Alexei Makarov,
minister-counselor of the Soviet Embassy. Matas said Makarov called
Wallenberg a hero and said he regrets what happened to him.
   B'nai B'rith asked the Soviets to appoint a commission of
historians from Canada, Hungary, Israel, Sweden, the Soviet Union
and the United States. The commission members would interview
surviving witnesses, review Soviet archives and make a public report.
   In 1944, Wallenberg volunteered for a mission to save Jews in
Budapest from Nazi death camps, and is credited with saving the Jews
from Nazi death camps by giving some Swedish passports, putting
others in safe houses and pleading with Nazi officials to spare
their lives.
   An estimated 6 million Jews were killed by the Nazis during their
1933-45 rule.
   If Wallenburg is alive, he would have been in captivity 43 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
