<FIRST>r a PM-SadlerProbate     01-14 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sadler Probate,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green Beret Ballad Singer Center Of Guardian Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A probate judge has ordered a psychiatric
evaluation of author, singer and songwriter Barry Sadler, who
suffered brain damage following a shooting in Guatemala last year.
   Sadler, 48, whose ``Ballad of the Green Berets'' was a No. 1 hit
in 1966, is at the center of a battle between his mother and his
son, who both want to become his legal guardian.
   Cuyahoga County Probate Judge John Donnelly on Friday filed a
temporary restraining order preventing Sadler from being moved
against his will from Cleveland. Donnelly said psychiatrist Kurt
Bertschinger will evaluate Sadler by Jan. 20 to determine whether he
is competent to make his own decisions.
   ``He will remain at Southwest General Hospital until he wants to
leave,'' Donnelly said.
   The judge said he will decide after the evaluation whether the
court has jurisdiction to appoint Sadler's mother as guardian.
   ``If he is competent, maybe we don't need a guardian,'' said
Donnelly, adding that Sadler's 24-year-old son, Thor, would be
allowed to visit his father.
   Davidson County Probate Judge James Everett of Nashville, Tenn.,
on Tuesday appointed the younger Sadler as temporary guardian, but
Donnelly said Everett agreed Friday to the psychiatric evaluation.
   Sadler, who was shot in the head in Guatemala City in September,
checked out of Cleveland's Veterans Administration hospital Sunday
against medical advice.
   He left after learning that hospital officials planned to send
him back to a Nashville VA hospital, said his attorney, Joseph
Meissner.
   Thor Sadler said 30 percent of his father's brain was damaged by
the bullet.
   Meissner said Friday that Sadler is mentally competent and wants
his mother, Blanche Bebe Sadler, appointed guardian to help him
conduct his affairs.
   A hearing is set in Nashville on Wednesday on a petition filed
Jan. 10 by Sadler's wife, Lavona Ruth, and children, Thor, Baron and
Brooke, asking the court to appoint one of them guardian and return
Sadler to Nashville.
   Guatemala City police reports indicate Sadler was shot by
accident when a gun fell out of his pocket and went off while he was
riding in a taxi, his son said.
   Sadler also is the author of more than 20 books, featuring Casca,
a mercenary condemned to everlasting life until the Second Coming of
Jesus Christ.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
