<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     01-14 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinian Girls Die Of Wounds, Mourners Stage Protest Srike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Palestinian girls died today from bullet
wounds suffered during clashes with Israeli troops, the army said,
bringing to four the number of Palestinians killed by army gunfire
in two days.
   Palestinian residents of Nablus, the largest city in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank, staged a mourning strike, and Arab
students left schools for marches to protest one of the killings,
said an Arab reporter there.
   Arab reports identified one of the victims as Hanadi Abu-Sultan.
The military command said the 12-year-old died at Israel's Tel
Hashomer Hospital after being shot Jan. 10 in a clash at Shati
refugee camp in Gaza City.
   In an apparent effort to prevent disturbances, the army clamped a
curfew on Shati, a beachside shantytown in Gaza City housing 42,000
Palestinians.
   Gaza merchants continued a commercial strike begun Friday to
protest Israeli raids to collect taxes. The strike was called by
PLO-linked leaders of the 13-month uprising. Non-payment of taxes is
a major tactic of the revolt against Israeli occupation.
   In east Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital, 14-year-old Rana Al-Masri
died of wounds from a Jan. 7 clash in Nablus, the army said. Arab
reports said she was shot in the head with a plastic bullet.
   At least seven other Palestinian teen-agers, aged 13 to 18, were
wounded today in stone-throwing clashes with troops, doctors at
Nasser Hospital said. They included one teen shot in the chest and
another transferred to Tel Hashomer in serious condition with a
bullet wound to the head.
   On Friday, a 15-year-old Palestinian died in Mukassed Hospital of
wounds from a Thursday clash with troops in Gaza's Nuseirat refugee
camp.
   Another 15-year-old Arab boy was killed Friday at Dheishe refugee
camp near Bethlehem, where dozens of youths hurled stones at troops
who responded with tear gas, rubber bullets and, finally, live
ammunition.
   Today's deaths raise to at least 355 the number of Arabs killed
in the uprising which started in December 1987. Fifteen Israelis
have died.
</TEXT>
