<DOCNO> AP890114-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     01-14 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Promises Afghan Government Continued Soviet Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Najib, one word, is correct.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
promised that his nation will give Afghanistan's beleaguered
government continued ``all-around assistance,'' Tass said today.
   The official Soviet news agency's report on talks between
Shevardnadze and Afghan President Najib appeared to indicate
Afghanistan will keep getting Soviet military aid, even after all
Red Army troops leave the country.
   Shevardnadze flew Friday to Kabul, Afghanistan's capital, as
Soviet officials continued working for a political solution
permitting them to withdraw their remaining 50,000 soldiers by Feb.
15.
   Soviet diplomats have hinted the Red Army may not complete with
withdrawal by the deadline, which was set at U.N.-brokered
negotiations in April 1988.
   Western diplomats, however, say the departure of Soviet troops
from Afghanistan, which was halted during the fall, has resumed.
   On Friday, reporters said 500 Soviet soldiers laden with military
equipment lined up before transport planes at Kabul airport, waiting
to fly home.
   The Soviets tried but failed to involve rebels fighting Najib's
government in peace talks with government representatives. Rebel
leaders say the Soviets only wanted to secure a place for Afghan
Marxists in a new Afghan government.
   Shevardnadze renewed the call for peace talks during his
discussions with Najib, but also clearly aligned himself with the
Afghan government, the Tass report indicated.
   ``The Soviet side confirmed its intention to continue playing an
intermediary role in launching a general dialogue in Afghanistan,''
Tass said.
   ``The Soviet side confirmed its full support for the Afghan
leadership's policies and said the Soviet Union will continue
extending the Republic of Afghanistan all-round assistance under
treaties and agreements concluded by the two countries,'' the news
agency said.
   Since the Soviets committed themselves to an Afghan withdrawal,
they have transferred millions of dollars worth of armaments and
military supplies to their Afghan allies, Western observers say.
   The Afghan government and the Soviets blame the guerrillas for
continuing hostilities because they have refused to join a
cease-fire proclaimed by Najib on Jan. 1.
   Soviet troops marched into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by another, and
the 100,000 soldiers stayed on to prop up the government against a
nationwide insurgency.
</TEXT>
