<DOCNO> AP890114-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Abrams-Successor Bjt   01-14 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abrams-Successor, Bjt,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Race for Key State Department Post Sets Capital Abuzz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elliott Abrams returns to private life next
week after 3{ tumultuous years as President Reagan's top aide for
Latin America, and much of the city's foreign policy establishment
is abuzz over the question of who will succeed him.
   Outside the cabinet itself, few presidential appointments have
generated more interest and curiosity about who President-elect Bush
will select for what is widely regarded as one of the toughest jobs
in government.
   The job carries an imposing title, assistant secretary of state
for inter-American affairs; a spacious paneled office on the sixth
floor of the State Department, and enough headaches to keep a
medium-sized pharmaceutical company in business. The task involves
dealing with issues ranging from drugs to debt in 33 hemispheric
countries.
   The Bush transition team is said by several sources to have
reduced the list of candidates to replace Abrams to five, four of
whom are foreign service officers.
   The only non-diplomat is Robert Helander, 67, a New York lawyer
who has had a long-time association with Rockefeller family business
interests in Latin America.
   But State Department officials said Helander's prospects seemed
to fade when he left an unfavorable impression on Capitol Hill
staffers during get-acquainted sessions earlier this month.
   The other candidates said to be on Bush's short list for Abrams'
job are:
   _Deane Hinton, ambassador to Costa Rica and a former ambassador
to El Salvador. One of his strengths is knowledge of economic issues
facing the hemisphere.
   _Everett Briggs, ambassador to Honduras who dealt with Central
American issues at the State Department during the early Reagan
years. He also was ambassador to Panama.
   _John Negroponte, a former ambassador to Honduras who serves as
deputy to National Security adviser Colin Powell. Some conservatives
oppose his appointment, contending his support for the Nicaraguan
Contras is only lukewarm.
   _Craig Johnstone, a former ambassador to Algeria who was the top
adviser on Central America under Abrams' predecessor, Tony Motley.
Johnstone has been actively pursuing the assistant secretary post
and has told friends he will leave the foreign service if the job
goes to someone else. He also has detractors in the conservative
camp.
   Much of the interest in the identity of Abrams' successor stems
from the uncertainty about the course Bush will follow on the two
dominant hemispheric issues: Central America and Latin America's
$420 billion foreign debt.
   Bush is expected to pursue a policy of continuity in most areas
of the world but he is considered by most experts as likely to try
new directions on Latin policy.
   The air of uncertainty has been fueled by the almost total
absence of discussion about Central America, particularly Nicaragua,
since well before the fall presidential election campaign.
   Once an issue of highest priority for the administration, Reagan
made no mention of Nicaragua or Central America in his summation
this past week of his eight years in office.
   Abrams, in a speech Thursday about the Reagan legacy in Latin
America, gave only a passing reference to Nicaragua and did not
mention the Contras at all.
   Bush will take office with the bulk of the Contra force stationed
at camps inside the Honduran border, surviving on U.S.-donated food
and other humanitarian supplies. Congress cut off military aid last
February and Bush has left unclear what plans he has for the Contras.
   Some transition team members have indicated privately that the
new administration may open talks with the Sandinista government, a
clear break with the Reagan policy of giving Managua the diplomatic
cold shoulder.
   One possible option for Bush would be to abandon the Reagan goal
of seeking a democratic outcome in Nicaragua and instead seek an
accommodation with the Sandinistas in return for promises of a
reduced Soviet-bloc role there.
   On the debt question, Bush has left the impression he will seek
new approaches that will have the effect of easing Latin repayment
obligations.
</TEXT>
