<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Quake Rescue, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tass Says Earthquake Rescue Story May Have Been A Hoax</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Tass saying story may be a hoax. No
pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass said today the story it ran about six men
rescued from a collapsed building 35 days after the Armenian
earthquake may have been a hoax.
   On Thursday, the official news agency quoted Aikaz Akopyan, 50,
as saying he and five other men were rescued Wednesday after
surviving on canned goods in a building that collapsed in Leninakan
during the Dec. 7 earthquake.
   On Friday, Tass reported it could not confirm Akopyan's story,
and today the news agency said Akopyan's sister indicated the story
was made up to get Akopyan into a good hospital in Yerevan, the
capital of Armenia.
   However, Tass said Akopyan was sticking to his story, that
doctors could not rule it out, and that reporters were still
checking details of the case.
   Tass said Akopyan had threatened to jump out the window of his
hospital room if journalists continued to question him about his
story and that doctors were taking the threat seriously.
   Reporters of the Armenian news agency Armenpress found Akopyan's
sister, Julietta, who allegedly had met him as he was rescued
Wednesday but then disappeared, Tass said.
   ``At first the sister denied being related to Akopyan but then
admitted that she took Aikaz to the Yerevan hospital and that he
indeed is her brother. It follows from her words that Aikaz turned
to her on Jan. 6 with a request to take him to a good Yerevan
hospital,'' Tass said.
   ``Along the road to Yerevan the legend of being saved after 35
days was supposedly thought up,'' Tass said.
   None of the other five people who allegedly were trapped in the
basement of a nine-story apartment building with Akopyan have been
found.
   Officials gave up hope weeks ago of finding more survivors in the
Dec. 7 quake, which killed 25,000 people. They began bulldozing the
ruins in Leninakan and other cities to prevent decaying bodies from
spreading disease.
   Tass said today that Professor Gurgen Badanyan, a leading Soviet
internal medicine specialist, believed Akopyan had been suffering
from chronic lung and heart deficiencies for at least several years.
   Akopyan was initially reported to be suffering from pneumonia.
   A psychiatric exam indicated that Akopyan is not mentally ill,
but doctors observed that he mixed up some facts including the names
of children and the number of people who were trapped with him.
   ``Doctors think this is possible as a result of strong
psychological stress. We decided to ask him a direct question: is he
really telling the truth. Akopyan said, `Yes,' and in a rather
mixed-up way repeated his first version,'' Tass correspondents
Kirill Dibrova and Alexander Shchglenko wrote.
   They said doctors ``do not reject the theoretical possibility''
that Akopyan had spent a month trapped in the basement.
   It added that ``today Akopyan told doctors that if journalists do
not leave him in peace, he will throw himself out the window.'' It
said doctors ``consider this threat fully possible.''
</TEXT>
