<FIRST>r a AM-PerpetualScholarship     01-14 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Perpetual Scholarship,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Univeristy to Decide if Heir Can Use 133-year-old Scholarship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even back when a loaf of bread cost a
couple of cents, it must have seemed like a bargain: Contribute
$100, and your sons, your grandsons, your great-grandsons, and so on
in perpetuity would get free tuition at Indiana University.
   Sixty-eight people took the school up on its offer back in 1856,
and a descendant of one of them is trying to get the school to make
good on the deal.
   Scott Raper is the first descendant of state Rep. Elias Abel, one
of the purchasers, to try to benefit from his
great-great-great-great-grandfather's investment.
   However, Indiana residents now pay about $1,100 a semester, not
$8 as in 1856, and the university is studying how it will handle the
family's claim.
   University counsel Cliff K. Travis says he will review the
request when he gets copies of wills and documents that establish a
line of succession for the scholarship.
   Raper, a 1988 graduate of Owen Valley High School in Spencer, is
majoring in business at Indiana, a state university that was founded
in 1820.
   His mother, Nancy Raper, said last week she has the documents
Travis says he needs, and threatened to sue the university if the
scholarship is not honored.
   Mrs. Raper said she has known about the scholarship since she was
a little girl, but considered the piece of paper as just a curiosity
until a year ago. Previous generations of Abel's descendants either
didn't go to school or included no sons. The scholarship specifies
male descendants because women were not admitted to the school back
when it was created.
   Mrs. Raper said when her mother died a year ago and her son was
making plans to attend Indiana, the significance of the scholarship
hit her. She consulted a lawyer, and decided to follow up on it.
   ``It's something that my great-great-great grandfather purchased
in the belief that his heirs would be taken care of,'' she said.
``He was a supporter of the university, and I'm sure $100 helped
tremendously at that time.''
   If the validity of the scholarship has to be decided in court,
Travis says, it would be the first time.
   He said similar requests have come up a few times over the
decades. But for at least 40 years they have been rejected for
in-state residents on the basis of a university ruling that
technically, nobody from Indiana pays tuition, only ``fees.''
Out-of-state residents are eligible for partial scholarships _ the
difference between in-state ``fees'' and whatever the total charged
to out-of-state residents is, the ruling stated.
   Whether that definition will be applied in Raper's case, in order
to disqualify him, is what university officials are trying to decide.
   But Mrs. Raper said her great-great-great grandfather would not
have purchased a perpetual scholarship if it were only intended to
pay out-of-state tuition.
   ``I just can't understand why he'd purchase something that would
be no good to him,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
