<FIRST>r a AM-People     01-14 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0925</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burt Reynolds' film crew found the
people living at a West Palm Beach home agreeable to blowing up
their front lawn for an episode of the ``B.L. Stryker'' television
series.
   Everything was fine _ until the owner of the home found out.
   When Daniel O'Brien of Ardsley, N.Y., learned that Reynolds'
production company was crashing cars in front of his house and had
given his living room the look of a motel, he called demanding
answers.
   ``They have no permission to do this,'' said O'Brien's son,
Kieran, from New York. Neither watched the filming in person.
   Blue Period Inc. said the company did have permission _ from
O'Brien's tenants, Ricardo and Laura Gonzalez, who signed an
agreement allowing the filming. Mrs. Gonzalez refused to answer
questions Friday.
   Officials of Reynolds' company said they were under the
impression the Gonzalezes owned the three-bedroom house until
O'Brien telephoned Friday morning.
   ``If we thought there was a problem, we could have gone to
another location and then found another house to shoot,'' said Rita
Duffy, assistant locations coordinator for the series. ``Burt has
always tried to be as cooperative as possible.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrity attorney Marvin Mitchelson, who put
``palimony'' in the lexicon of domestic breakups, has been ordered
to pay Sotheby's auction house interest on nearly $1 million worth
of jewelry for which he has not yet paid, as well as attorneys' fees.
   Mitchelson was ordered Friday to pay interest from April 9, 1987,
the day he took possession, rather than Oct. 21, 1988, the day he
claims the money was due.
   U.S. District Judge James Ideman on Friday also ordered
Mitchelson to pay Sotheby's $100,000 in attorneys' fees.
   The jewelry was once owned by the Duchess of Windsor. Mitchelson
bid on them at auction in Geneva in April 1987.
   Mitchelson has not paid for the gems because he does not have the
money, according to his attorney, Harold Rhoden, who said the ruling
means Mitchelson owes $200,000 in interest.
   ``Palimony'' was the legacy of Mitchelson's work for Michelle
Triola Marvin in suing her former live-in boyfriend, actor Lee
Marvin, in 1976.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARK CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers skiing in the 3rd Annual
Senator's Ski Cup were in light spirits as they helped Sen. Jake
Garn, R-Utah, raise money for Salt Lake City's Primary Children's
Medical Center.
   Seventeen senators and two members of President-elect George
Bush's Cabinet skied Friday. Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the
Armed Services Committee, said he was a beginning skier.
   ``If you could handicap my skiing like you do golf, I'd be skiing
about a 120,'' he joked.
   Joseph Biden, D-Del., an early contender in the 1988 race for the
Democratic presidential nomination, dismissed claims he was the
favorite in the ski race.
   ``That's what they said about the Democratic nomination,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mop-topped, seventh-grader Adam Guier will
spend the next two months playing the lead in a movie about the
childhood of basketball star ``Pistol'' Pete Maravich.
   The northwest Louisiana youth was one of five finalists screened
by Maravich more than a year ago.
   Maravich, the leading scorer in college basketball history and a
member of the NBA Hall of Fame, died in January 1988 from a heart
attack during a pickup basketball game in California.
   The 12-year-old will begin work on the film Feb. 5 in Baton
Rouge. ``Pistol'' is being filmed by independent filmmaker Peter
Andrews of the Louisiana Production Group.
   Guier has been practicing ball-handling drills for about four
years _ ever since his father put up a basketball goal in the
backyard. One of the tricks that young Guier and Maravich both
mastered at the age of 12 is dribbling with either hand while riding
a bicycle.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson has sued the owners of
an Inglewood video store, alleging they are selling unauthorized
copies of the ``common ground'' speech he made to the Democratic
Convention last summer.
   The federal copyright infringement case asks the court to
prohibit sales of the Jackson video at the Cable Via Satellite store
and to award the former Democratic presidential candidate
unspecified punitive damages.
   The lawsuit filed by attorney Donald L. Samuels names Charles
Cordell Conrad and Dezella Banks as defendants.
   Conrad, who was reached by telephone at the store, denied he is
selling the tapes, saying they may have been sold by Banks, who he
said was an independent contractor who was ``selling things on his
own.''
   He also denied the lawsuit's charge that he and Banks are the
same person.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Max, the graphic artist whose
psychedelic style inspired the Beatles' Yellow Submarine, has
donated a painting to a Los Angeles tree-planting campaign.
   Mayor Tom Bradley accepted the painting portraying two trees
Friday on behalf of TreePeople, a Los Angeles-based conservation
group that is organizing a program to plant as many as 5 million
trees across the nation's second-largest city over the next five
years.
   TreePeople officials said they haven't decided yet what to do
with the painting, but it may be used as a symbol for the planting
campaign or sold to raise money for the effort.
   Bradley proclaimed Friday ``Peter Max Day'' in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
