<FIRST>r a AM-BatteryAward     01-14 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battery Award,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Awarded Total $9.7 Million in Car Battery Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who tried to help an elderly couple
jump-start their car has been awarded $6.5 million in punitive
damages for injuries he suffered when the battery exploded.
   The jury's action Friday against Johnson Controls Inc., the
manufacturer of Sears Die-Hard batteries, raised to $9.7 million the
total damages awarded to Gary Jones, 34, and his wife, Mona, of
Redding.
   On Thursday, the Superior Court jury found Johnson Controls Inc.
and the distributor, Sears Roebuck &amp; Co. Inc., liable for $3.2
million in general damages. The general damages covered Jones'
injuries, medical costs and lost wages.
   The jury's finding on punitive damages singled out Johnson
Controls because attorneys for the Joneses contended that the
company knew about the battery's defective design but did not warn
consumers.
   Attorneys for Johnson Controls said an appeal is planned.
   Jones, a former banquet chef, tried to help an elderly couple
jump-start their car in June 1986 across the street from the La
Jolla campus of the University of California at San Diego.
   Jones testified during the six-week trial that as soon as the
engine turned over, the Sears Die-Hard battery exploded.
   ``I was blown from the car and I screamed for someone to call an
ambulance,'' said Jones, who lost an eye and suffers seizures.
   An attorney for the couple, Harvey Levine, said he hoped Johnson
Controls would recall the batteries or at least warn customers of
the jump-start danger.
   The design of the battery was changed in 1985.
</TEXT>
