<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceRequest     01-14 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Request,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer Offers Wheat To Soviets For Space Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oklahoma farmer says he has offered the
Soviet Union $1 million worth of wheat in exchange for a seat on a
Soviet space flight.
   Even if the Soviets accept his offer, 73-year-old Elmer Graham
still has to convince his wife, Mary Ruth.
   ``She raises hell every time I get on one of these tears,''
Graham said in a telephone interview.
   The southern Oklahoma farmer and banker said he wrote Soviet
Ambassador Yuri Dubinin on Nov. 30 offering the deal. He hasn't had
a reply, but he thinks that is a good sign.
   ``If they were going to turn it down, they would have just
flat-footed done it,'' Graham said. ``I figure they're checking me
out, making sure I'm not with the CIA or something like that.'
   He said he did not apply to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration for a space flight.
   ``I'd a heap lot rather go up with the United States, but they
quit that after that accident,'' he said, referring to the
Challenger disaster that killed seven astronauts.
   Graham, who says he farms several thousand acres of land, also is
board chairman of two southern Oklahoma banks. He said he personally
doesn't have the $1 million worth of wheat, ``but I've got friends
who have offered to lend me what I need.''
 
</TEXT>
