<FIRST>u w AM-InauguralRdp 1stadd 1stLd-Writethru 01-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inaugural Rdp, 1st add, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0523,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 1st graf this take to CORRECT date to 1829 sted 1929</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: South Lawn, too.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The last president to hold an open house was William Howard Taft,
80 years ago. But the most memorable occasion was in 1829, when
thousands of Tennessee frontiersmen and Indian fighters in muddy
boots followed one of their own, Andrew Jackson, right into the
White House. Many stood on the pastel upholsteries of fine damask
and satin just to get a better view; others shattered china and
glassware after too much refreshment.
   Most new presidents, of course, would prefer that their
inaugurals be remembered, not for the whirlwind of celebration, but
for their calls to the nation's conscience, those ringing words of
wisdom to set America on an ever brighter course. But there have
been more thuds, than rings, especially in this century.
   Still, the nation embraces with special fondness the words of
Franklin Delano Roosevelt to a Depression-stricken country in 1933:
``The only thing we have to fear is fear itself.'' And then there
were those of a Democrat from Massachusetts, who unlike Michael
Dukakis, managed to defeat an incumbent vice president for the White
House. ``Ask not ...'' said John Kennedy.
   Bush probably will have his moments. But first he may want,
simply, to take in the view. The departing tenant, Ronald Reagan,
put it this way, by way of defining the job Bush has had the last
eight years: ``The vice presidency ... is described by an old rule
of dog-sledding _ only the lead dog gets a change of scenery.''
</TEXT>
