<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Shultz     01-14 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resolution Of Territorial Dispute Clears Way For Last Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will embark
on his last overseas trip Sunday, a visit to Vienna to wind up a
35-nation human rights conference and set the stage for East-West
arms control talks.
   While in the Austrian capital, Shultz also will hold a 32nd and
final meeting with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Shultz plans to return to Washington on Tuesday after making a
speech to the conference. He will leave office three days later, to
be succeeded by James A. Baker III, assuming Senate confirmation,
and fly home to Palo Alto, Calif.
   The trip had been on hold until Greece and Turkey settled a
dispute over how much Turkish territory would be included in arms
control negotiations between the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
and the Warsaw Pact.
   In 6{ years, Shultz, 68, has flown more than 1 million miles on
diplomatic missions. On this one he will spend about 18 hours in the
air and about 32 hours on the ground.
   The Vienna conference has run for 27 months. Its windup first was
delayed until the Reagan administration was satisfied with the
reforms the Soviet Union had made in human rights. The release of
more than 600 political prisoners, reunification of more than 100
divided families and a nine-year high in Jewish emigration met the
U.S. test.
   As a result, Shultz recommended and President Reagan approved the
holding of another human rights review in Moscow in 1991 and the
closing down of the Vienna conference.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze, both instrumental in the improvement in
U.S.-Soviet relations, will discuss preparations for the arms
control talks and probably the scheduled Feb. 15 completion of a
Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   The United States was not directly involved in the dispute
between Greece and Turkey, but worked behind the scenes for a
resolution. Yuri Dubinin, the Soviet ambassador to Washington,
called on Shultz late Thursday to discuss the situation.
</TEXT>
