<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-Text     01-14 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Text,850</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's radio address Saturday, as given by Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn.:
   Good afternoon. I'm Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut. As a newly
elected senator, I am especially honored to be asked by Sen. George
Mitchell to follow this final weekly radio address of President
Ronald Reagan.
   Over the last several years, we Democrats have used this time to
provide constructive alternatives to the policies of the president
and his party.
   But today, we join with all Americans in honoring and
appreciating his stewardship of the highest office in our land.
   Mr. President, we salute you. Your love of this country and your
fervent devotion to freedom inspired us all. You raised the spirit
of America, and upheld the values of faith, flag and family that we
hold so dear.
   I believe that is why, after eight years, Mr. President, you are
even more popular with the American people than on the day you were
sworn in. Some politicians might find that fact frustrating, but we
all should be grateful for it. For without the respect of the
people, the president would be powerless, and our country would be
left at risk.
   ``America is freedom,'' President Reagan said in his farewell
address this week. As a person whose grandparents came to this
country to escape persecution abroad and just last week was sworn in
as a United States senator, I know how real the American promise of
freedom and opportunity still is.
   But I also know that along with opportunity comes challenge, and
that is what confronts us now at the end of the Reagan era and the
beginning of the Bush administration, the challenge and opportunity
of our future.
   We are challenged to protect our nation's security while we
pursue the opportunity for peace with the Soviet Union.
   We are challenged to end the plague of drugs and crime, while we
endeavor to provide opportunity for our young people to become
educated, and trained to join our workforce.
   We are challenged to reduce the federal deficit while opening
opportunities for those afflicted with disease or burdened by
poverty.
   But perhaps our greatest new challenge in the years ahead will
come from the natural environment that delimits our world and
defines the quality of our lives.
   When the pilgrim John Winthrop envisioned the shining city upon
the hill, of which the president speaks so eloquently, he looked out
upon a continent untouched by smog, hazardous waste and acid rain.
In the centuries since that pristine age, we have conquered the
continent, but we have also made it dirty and unsafe.
   The industrial revolution has swept the world, but we haven't
swept up behind it. Now the decades of neglect have come back to
haunt us, and threaten to engulf our children's future, and endanger
their health and safety.
   If we do not meet this challenge, we may face disaster. Holes in
the ozone layer and acid in the rain will cause skin cancer and lung
disease.
   Gases in the air will warm the planet and lead to drought in our
heartland and flooding along our coast.
   Waste in our water will make our beaches forbidding places to
visit on a summer's day.
   But there is hope, and it lies, as President Reagan would say,
with ``we the people.'' The protection of the environment will be
high on the agenda of the new Congress and the new president not
because it makes political sense, but because the people know it
makes common sense.
   People like Rico and Annette Gattilia of North Haven, Conn., who
built a grass roots environmental movement from the living room of
their modest home. A movement that does battle with the large
chemical company that pollutes the air in their own backyard and
dirties the river where once they would fish and swim.
   Government can't do everything; it must have limits, as President
Reagan has said. But one of the things it can and must do is protect
the health and safety of our people. Elimination of pollution in our
water, on our land and in the air is a responsibility we in
government cannot shirk. The people will not allow us to.
   As President Reagan's time in Washington comes to an end and my
service in the Senate here just begins, I must say that I am
encouraged and inspired by his sense of patriotism and hope. It
moves and binds us all across generations and ideologies, because it
is born of shared pride in country, belief in God, and a sense of
duty to the people.
   So let us now set out to work on the unfinished business of
America with the spirit of purpose and confidence that is the legacy
of the Reagan years. It is, after all, the same spirit that built
this country and will if we protect it, continue to make us a truly
great nation.
</TEXT>
