<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   01-14 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghans Glad to Bid Adieu to Soviets, But Worried About Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing stoically in line for heating
fuel, Sadrahmah Bikhar mused on the pullout of Soviet troops, saying
simply, ``It's good; I don't like them.''
   It's hard to find anyone who does on the streets of this bleak
capital ringed by snowy hills.
   In random interviews with The Associated Press, most people were
openly hostile toward the Soviets. But asked about the survival
prospects of President Najib's Marxist government, many glanced
uneasily at the interpreter and bystanders and make noncommittal
replies.
   Instead, they expressed hope _ but little belief _ that the
fighting will end when the Soviets leave.
   Their reluctance to answer certain questions is understandable.
In this divided land, official rhetoric remains upbeat, although it
contrasts sharply with reality.
   On Saturday, anti-government guerrillas, known as Mujahadeen,
attacked a 400-vehicle government supply and ammunition convoy four
miles from Kabul.
   Western reporters saw Afghan units dig in on both sides of the
Solang highway, a key northern route, and heard rocket fire before
government troops opened fire into the hills and the convoy raced
past.
   The same day, the state-run Kabul Times published new triumphant
exhortations from the Soviet-backed Marxist administration. In a
report on celebrations for the ninth anniversary of the founding of
the Ministry of State Security, it said Gen. Ghulam Farouq Yaqubi
welcomed Najib, declaring, ``We feel ourselves more powerful than
ever against the thievish attacks of the intransigent extremists.''
   On the streets, Bikhar's several-hour wait reflected the
increasing harassment of the convoys running three times a week on
the Solang, now the sole highway supplying the city.
   As the Soviets have moved out their forces to meet a U.N.
deadline for pulling out all their troops by Feb. 15, guerrillas
have approached the capital and stepped up convoy attacks.
   Bikhar said all he knew was that things were getting worse. Asked
what he thought would happen when all the Soviets were gone, he
shrugged and said through an interpreter, ``I don't know. I hope the
fighting will stop.''
   But there was no doubt in the mind of Eshaqza Anargul, a mechanic
with the state-owned Afghan Airline, Ariana.
   ``There will be fighting for another 10 years, maybe longer,'' he
said.
   ``Economically, it will get worse too,'' he added.
   Armed opposition to the government began soon after it invited
the Soviet troops in 1979 in the wake of a Soviet-backed coup. Since
then, the war has killed an estimated 1 million people, driven a
third of the 15 million Afghans to Pakistan and Iran, and scarred
millions more.
   Amputees are a common sight on the streets of Kabul. Tales abound
of family members _ troops, guerrillas, and civilians _ killed or
missing.
   Abdul Salom, a turbaned 60-year-old, said he fled his village of
Saraikhoga, 50 miles from Kabul, after it was damaged in bombing
attacks against rebels. He has squeezed into a mud house with
relatives in the Kharkhana district of Kabul.
   The area is a mixture of bleak , concrete six-story apartments
and slums of mud houses without heat, electricity or water. Salom
squats under a blanket in a friend's shop _ a cargo container turned
into a makeshift store selling soap, nails, and other items.
   He is one of about 1 million refugees who have doubled the prewar
population of the capital.
   ``We just want peace,'' he said. ``No Russians, no Mujahadeen, no
government, just peace.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
