<DOCNO> AP890114-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Crash     01-14 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Crash,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tape From Cockpit Recorder Inconclusive, Investigators Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The comments on the flight
recorder of a South African Airways plane that crashed in 1987 have
not produced the information investigators sought, the government
said Saturday.
   The Boeing 747 was traveling from Taipei, Taiwan, to Johannesburg
when it crashed into the Indian Ocean on Nov. 28, 1987, just prior
to a scheduled stop on the island nation of Mauritius. All 159
people on board were killed.
   South Africa has not given an explanation for the crash and has
refused to release the tape recordings of conversations between the
cabin crew and the control tower. It also has not said what
information it was hoping to get from the recording.
   The government launched a $6 million salvage operation that found
the recorder Jan. 6 off the coast of Mauritius, 2.5 miles underwater.
   The recorder was sent to the U.S. National Transportation Safety
Board in Washington where investigators listened to the tape last
week.
   The tape was audible but has not provided the information
investigators were seeking, the South African Department of
Transport said Saturday. It said it will continue to search for
unspecified pieces of the wreckage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
