<FIRST>r a AM-ProtestedKill     01-14 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Protested Kill,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Held Down While Officials Kill Wounded Antelope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASPER, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal rights activist whose dog mauled a
young antelope had to be restrained by a game warden while a state
biologist tried to kill the wounded animal by hitting it over the
head with heavy pliers.
   Game Warden Lin Robinson said she stopped Carol Gauden from
interfering with Wyoming Game and Fish Department biologist Rich
Guenzel's attempts to kill the fawn.
   ``I was giving the fencing pliers to Rich to go ahead and
dispatch it while I was starting to walk way with her. She kind of
shoved me and grabbed me and we ended up on the ground and I sat on
her,'' Robinson said.
   Gauden, of Casper, had been walking with her dog in snow-covered
Crossroads Park Thursday when the dog attacked the antelope. She
called the Game and Fish Department for assistance.
   When Robinson and Guenzel arrived they told her the animal was
near death and would have to be killed, Gauden said.
   She offered to pay for the animal's care and let it graze on her
20 acres of land while it recovered. But the officers said the
antelope wouldn't survive well in care, Gauden said.
   Guenzel tried to kill the antelope with the pliers. The animal
didn't die after the first few blows so Robinson slit its throat.
   ``It's the first animal I've seen destroyed that way that didn't
immediately die,'' Robinson said.
   The antelope was badly injured, showing signs of heavy internal
bleeding, and had no chance of survival, she said. It had bite marks
from the ears to the shoulder blades, punctured intestinal walls and
a hide-torn rump.
</TEXT>
