<FIRST>r a AM-King-Memphis     01-14 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King-Memphis,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groundbreaking Delayed for Memorial to King at Motel Where He Was
Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King's Church, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The motel where Martin Luther King Jr. was
slain has been a focal point for past celebrations, but will not be
part of the city's major tributes to the civil rights leader Monday.
   The Lorraine Motel, where King was killed by an assassin's bullet
in 1968, is to become the centerpiece of an $8.8 million civil
rights museum. The crumbling motel has been surrounded for most of
the past year by a chain-link fence.
   King was born Jan. 15, 1929, and the national holiday honoring
him is Monday. Promoters of the Lorraine museum had planned to stage
a groundbreaking ceremony for the project on the holiday, but it has
been delayed until Jan. 27.
   ``The state needed more time to line up the worker crews that are
to begin work that day,'' said D'Army Bailey, president of a
non-profit foundation that took up donations to buy The Lorraine at
a foreclosure auction in 1982.
   As the Lorraine museum project prepares to go forward, another
King institution is undergoing a transition.
   Coretta Scott King, the civil rights leader's widow, will step
down as president of The King Center on April 4, to be replaced by
her son, Dexter Scott King, directors of the Atlanta-based memorial
and policy center announced Saturday.
   Mrs. King will stay on as chief executive officer and
spokesperson for the center, which is devoted to spreading the
activist's non-violent policies worldwide.
   In Memphis, speeches and memorial services are planned at various
locations, including Clayborn Temple, where King helped organize a
sanitation workers' strike.
   He was killed while in town to help lead that protest. In past
years members of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees have gathered at The Lorraine to lay a wreath in
King's honor.
   ``They've got so much stuff going on down here now, I don't think
we need to go down (to the Lorraine). In fact, we can't even get on
the premises,'' said the Rev. James Smith, president of the
federation's Local 1733.
   The museum project, with funding from the city, county and state,
should be finished in 1991, Bailey said.
   The Lorraine Civil Rights Museum Foundation plans to turn over
title to the motel to the state so it can maintain and run the
museum. However, Muhammad Ziad, leader of an organization called The
Poor People's Campaign, filed a lawsuit last week to keep the state
from taking over the building.
   He said in the Chancery Court lawsuit that people who gave money
to save the motel should be polled to see what they think about the
project.
   While the major King day events will be held elsewhere, a Memphis
group called the Commission On Religion and Racism has scheduled a
march to the motel.
   The march is dedicated to Jacqueline Smith, who has camped out on
a sidewalk beside the Lorraine since being evicted from the motel in
March to make way for the museum project.
   Miss Smith, a former Lorraine employee, contends the project is
part of an effort to gentrify the neighborhood, which is dominated
by warehouses and rundown rental property. She also has said the
memorial would focus on the violence of King's death rather than the
peacefulness of his message.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
