<DOCNO> AP890114-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1620EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0543 01-14 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0543,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Saturday's Will Never Seem The Same,'' President Says In Last Radio
Talk</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts graf 7, ``Several hours xxx to update with departure
for Camp David</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan delivered his 331st, and last,
radio address as president on Saturday, telling his listeners he was
grateful to have played a part in ``the story of a people and a
cause ... the American saga.''
   ``Believe me, Saturdays will never seem the same. I'll miss
you,'' the president said as he read his five-minute address from
the Oval Office.
   ``Over the years I've greatly enjoyed this opportunity to get
together with you, and report on the week's events here in
Washington,'' said the one-time radio sportscaster and Hollywood
actor.
   He started the Saturday series on April 3, 1982.
   Reagan noted that he and his wife Nancy planned to return home to
California after the inauguration of President-elect Bush on Friday.
   ``We go with full hearts, with best wishes for George and Barbara
and with gratitude to all of you. It's been a privilege to serve the
people and the nation we've always loved, and loved so much today,''
Reagan said. ``We shared a great deal together. For me, it's been a
special relationship.''
   Several hours after delivering his address, Reagan and his wife
Nancy departed for an overnight stay at the presidential retreat in
Camp David. In a first, the president and his wife traveled aboard a
new, $14 million Sikorski helicopter that has been designed for
presidential use. The sleek new craft is to be used for shorter
distances and on international trips because it is small enough to
be transported overseas in cargo aircraft.
   In his radio address, the president said he wasn't leaving with a
downcast spirit, asserting that the economy was booming, the
nation's social problems were being dealt with and ``the Soviet
menace shows some sign of relenting.''
   Reagan said his eight-year presidency was only part of ``a far
larger story, the story of a people and a cause ... the hope of
human freedom, the quest for it, the achievement of it, is the
American saga.''
   ``Whether we seek it or not, whether we like it or not, we
Americans are keepers of the miracle. We are asked to be guardians
of a place to come to, a place to start again, a place to live in
the dignity God meant for his children. May it ever be so,'' Regan
said.
   The president began his script with the traditional greeting,
``My fellow Americans,'' and ended it as he always has: ``Thanks for
listening. And God bless you.''
   Reagan's first job was as a sports broadcaster in Davenport,
Iowa, and radio gave him the exposure that helped him launch a
career in Hollywood.
   As an actor-turned-politician, Reagan honed his radio style for
use as a political tool during his days as the governor of
California.
   Over the years, it has been difficult to calculate how many
people hear the president's live, noontime address, since many of
the radio networks that have carried it only ``feed'' it to their
subscribers, who either replay it at their leisure or do not air it
at all.
   The only time the president was assured his voice would be
carried came during the 1984 campaign, when his campaign purchased
the air time.
   The president personally chose themes for his addresses.
   Occasionally, he dominated the news, as on the Saturday he used
the folksy-style addresses to announce the reappointment of Federal
Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker, or the time he announced suspension
of a preferential trading status for Poland in the wake of the
communist government's suppression of the Solidarity labor union.
   Reagan's most infamous remarks came outside the formal radio
address, when he announced prior to one speech from his ranch in
California that he had ``just signed legislation that will outlaw
Russia forever. The bombing begins in five minutes.''
   The president has a habit of joking with his aides prior to the
talk, and the remarks were made during a voice check when the
microphone was turned on but he was not yet on the air. The remarks
were heard by the radio ``pool'' that was transmitting it to the
other networks.
</TEXT>
