<FIRST>r w AM-Gulf-Ships     01-14 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Ships,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Reduces Persian Gulf Force Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. naval force in the Persian Gulf is
being trimmed again, leaving the fleet with six surface fighting
ships, the lowest number since the mid-1987 buildup that began as
the Iraq-Iran war escalated.
   As the missile cruiser USS Josephus Daniels and three missile
frigates departed the Gulf in recent days, three newly arriving
vessels entered the waterway to begin their three-month duty tours.
   The three-for-four swap effectively reduced the Gulf-based fleet
from 15 to 14 ships and pared the number of surface combatants _
cruisers, destroyers and frigates _ from seven to six.
   The total of 14 is the lowest number of American warships in the
Gulf since July 1987. It also includes six minesweepers, an
amphibious landing ship that serves as their ``mother ship'' and the
USS La Salle, flagship of the Joint Task Force Middle East.
   Another ten ships, a battle group built around the
nuclear-powered aircraft carrier USS Nimitz, remains on station in
the Arabian Sea. It is to be replaced by another carrier group,
headed by the USS Constellation, at the end of the month.
   The force inside the Gulf is slowly being reduced in strength
following the Iraq-Iran cease-fire that went into effect last
August. But U.S. military sources say a carrier group will be
operating in the Indian Ocean and Arabian Sea for the foreseeable
future.
   The Defense Department said in a statement Friday that the
Josephus Daniels was being withdrawn because it was ``no longer
required to meet the threat to our forces and shipping in the
region.''
   In fact, the departure of the Daniels did not reflect a sudden
decision to reduce the force. The 8,200-ton cruiser, based at
Norfolk, Va., was scheduled to leave the Gulf on Jan. 8, along with
three other East Coast-based ships, the frigates Aubrey Fitch, Doyle
and Taylor.
   As those four ships sailed out of the Gulf in recent days, their
patrol responsibilities were taken over by the destroyer O'Bannon
and the frigates Hawes and De Wert, all based at Charleston, S.C.
   The frigate Klakring, originally slated for deployment along with
those three, had its orders cancelled in December. Officials said at
the time that the resulting force reduction of one ship was seen as
a ``prudent move ... considering the situation'' since the
cease-fire.
   With the arrival of the newcomers, the mix in the Gulf includes
the Hawes, the De Wert and another missile frigate, the Reid, as
well as the O'Bannon and another destroyer, the Harry W. Hill, plus
the missile cruiser England.
   The United States earlier scaled back its operations in the Gulf
from direct escorting of U.S.-flagged tankers to a system of
``monitoring'' their movements from a distance.
   It also has curtailed air patrols and, according to the Pentagon
on Friday, recently withdrew one of the four AWACs, or airborne
surveillance aircraft, based in Saudi Arabia during the last year of
the Iraq-Iran war.
   There have been no armed incidents in the Gulf since the United
Nations-brokered truce went into effect Aug. 20, and other foreign
navies have been pulling out their forces.
   Britain disclosed earlier in the week that it planned to withdraw
its last three minesweepers by March, leaving it with a three-ship
patrol unit. Italy, Belgium and the Netherlands are withdrawing
entirely, and the French have cut their regional force to reflect
the reduced tensions in the waterway since the 8-year war ended.
   Although the cease-fire has worked, U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
C. Carlucci said during a visit to the Gulf on Dec. 5 that there was
``no plan for major changes in our force structure'' as long as
Baghdad and Tehran failed to make any progress toward a negotiated
peace.
   U.S. officials have made it clear that the United States would
continue to maintain a permanent force in the Gulf, at least at the
level of four to six warships that were assigned there before the
1987 buildup.
   The continued presence of a Soviet fleet, some seven to ten
warships, is seen as an important factor affecting the rate at which
the United States will reduce its Gulf force, U.S. military sources
say.
   In any case, those sources say, any cutbacks would not include
the six minesweepers sent to the Gulf in late 1987 to deal with a
growing threat of mines planted by Iran in shipping lanes.
   U.S. officials insist that a mine threat still exists, mainly in
the northern Gulf, and the Navy is still debating what to do with
the wooden-hulled, Korean War vintage minesweepers.
</TEXT>
