<FIRST>u w AM-Nancy'sFarewell 1stLd-Writethru a0512 01-14 1169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nancy's Farewell, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,1,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>``I Hope I'm Remembered For The Drug Program And The Help To Children''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``I've very...'' to CORRECT to ``I'm
very...''; picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Her voice...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto WX6, LaserColor WX7. ^By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Nancy Reagan prepares to leave the pomp and
pageantry of eight years in the White House, she wants to be
remembered for her work against drug abuse rather than her penchant
for borrowing high-priced, designer gowns.
   ``I'm very happy that I was able to help the (fashion) industry,
but I hope that's not the thing I'm remembered for. I hope I'm
remembered for the drug program and the help to children,'' the
first lady said.
   Her voice reduced to a mere whisper by a severe bout of
laryngitis, Mrs. Reagan reviewed the ups and downs of her years in
Washington in a 45-minute farewell interview on Thursday with The
Associated Press.
   Sipping coffee from a delicate white and gold china cup in the
Yellow Oval Room of the mansion's private quarters, Mrs. Reagan
discussed the disclosure that she had ignored the pledge she made in
1982 to abstain from borrowing high-priced designer clothes and
gowns.
   ``I was just trying to help an industry that I could help and I
was in the position to help. I didn't see anything wrong with
that,'' Mrs. Reagan said.
   Mrs. Reagan noted that America's top designers have given her
their ``Lifetime Achievement Award'' for her contribution to the
fashion industry.
   ``Whenever anybody talked about fashion, they would think French,
Dior, whatever. They never thought about American. Well, now
American designers are taken seriously abroad. There is a
competition that is just wonderful,'' the first lady said.
   Attempting to counter critics who have said her actions amounted
to free advertising for several of her favorite designers, Mrs.
Reagan insisted: ``I wasn't advertising for these people. I was
trying to promote and help one of the biggest industries in our
country. ... They are all very grateful, and nobody saw anything
wrong with it.''
   Turning to the work she wants to be identified with, Mrs. Reagan
said she has had some silent victories in her battle against drug
abuse, receiving ``a lot of letters from kids ... or parents that
I've been able to help'' in instances that few people know about.
   She said she regretted that ``there's always those kids that you
haven't been able to get to, and you haven't been able to reach.''
She added that she intended to keep working through the anti-drug
abuse center named after her that is to be built near Los Angeles.
   ``I don't believe in retirement,'' she said.
   Mrs. Reagan said she was saddened to learn that Jason Brady, a
16-year-old suffering from cancer who had visited her a week before
Christmas through the ``Make-A-Wish'' foundation, had died.
   ``He said he wanted to come here ... he said, `I've seen you on
television, and I want to tell you that I admire you, and I know
that you've been a great support to your husband,''' she said, her
voice softening. ``He died on Christmas Day.''
   Queried about criticism from consumer advocate Ralph Nader that
she and President Reagan have not included warnings against tobacco
in their lectures against drug abuse, Mrs. Reagan held up a finger
for emphasis. ``I agree with him,'' she said. ``It's as addictive as
any of the other drugs, (including) alcohol.''
   The first lady went on to say she hoped one of her aides, a
smoker who was present in the room, ``is listening.'' Mrs. Reagan
has been known to rigorously keep after White House personnel who
smoke, insisting they get help to kick their habit.
   Looking back over her eight years in the White House, Mrs. Reagan
said she had not anticipated that life in the executive mansion
``would be as confining'' as it turned out to be. ``Certainly after
Ronnie's shooting, (in March 1981) everything tightened up,'' she
said.
   ``It always bothered Ronnie that he created such a to-do when we
went to a restaurant. And this entourage of cars _ that always
bothered him,'' Mrs. Reagan said of the 20-plus vehicles that the
Secret Service organizes for a presidential motorcade.
   President-elect Bush and his wife Barbara are expected to keep up
their active social life, and Mrs. Reagan said she hoped ``they'll
find their own way'' to get out and about, despite security concerns.
   Mrs. Reagan said she and her husband ``are happy'' they will
continue to receive Secret Service protection after they leave the
White House.
   One subject Mrs. Reagan refused to discuss was former Reagan
chief of staff Donald T. Regan's revelation that she had used an
astrologer to help formulate the president's schedule. ``Read my
book,'' she quipped, promising to deal with the subject in her
memoirs, which she said are due out in the fall.
   Of Regan, who blamed the first lady for organizing his ouster in
the wake of allegations he had mismanaged the White House during the
Iran-Contra affair, Mrs. Reagan was curt.
   Asked if Reagan was happy with his former aide, Mrs. Reagan said
simply, ``He's not.'' Asked if she'd changed her mind about Regan,
who was harshly critical of her involvement in White House affairs
in his book, ``For the Record,'' she whispered, ``No.''
   Of the ``kiss-and-tell'' books that many Reagan aides have
written, Mrs. Reagan said she finds them to be ``reckless kinds of
books.''
   ``I think they're terrible. ... there's an implied trust, and
when you leave and write these books, you're breaking that trust,''
she said.
   The first lady said she has a formula for dealing with such
books, including any that come out in the future.
   ``I won't read them,'' she said, with stern look. ``I haven't
read any of the others.''
   The first lady said the barrage of criticism she'd encountered
upon entering the White House _ spurred by stories about her
privately-funded purchases of $209,000 of new china and a $730,000
redecoration of the White House _ had been ``a big surprise.''
   ``I had one disadvantage that Ronnie didn't have. I came in with
terrible press,'' she said. ``I never had that before. ... It made
me pull back. ... There was a hurdle on both sides .. you all
getting to know me and my getting to be a little hesitant, afraid.''
   Even eight years later, Mrs. Reagan still appeared upset about
reports that she wanted President Carter and his wife Rosalynn to
move out of the White House prior to the Reagan inauguration. ``I
never said that,'' Mrs. Reagan said, again her finger pointing for
emphasis.
   As she rose to leave, Mrs. Reagan was eager to offer some ``word
of wisdom'' for future first ladies, as well as all married women:
``Do your own thing. Don't be afraid to give your opinion. Just
because you're married doesn't mean you've given up your right to
have an opinion.''
</TEXT>
