<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Trial     01-14 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Trial,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Terrorists Sentenced to Life For Renault Assassination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Saturday convicted four leading members of a
left-wing terrorist group of murdering French industrialist Georges
Besse and sentenced them to life in prison.
   Nathalie Menigon, 31 and Joelle Aubron, 28, were convicted of
carrying out the shooting death of the Renault chief on Nov. 17,
1986. Menigon's companion, Jean-Marc Rouillan, 33, and Georges
Cipriani, 38, were convicted of complicity.
   Seven judges, concurring to demands of State Prosecutor Galiber
d'Auque, ruled the four must spend at least 18 years behind bars
before they are eligible for parole.
   The panel, which sits only on terrorism cases, deliberated for 75
minutes after hearing five days of testimony.
   The defendants had boycotted the court since the second day of
the trial. None was present when the verdict was read.
   All four are top members of Direct Action, which started as a
French group that bombed French institutions, usually during the
night when buildings were empty and no one could be hurt.
   But over the last few years, a deadly European branch has evolved
with links to West Germany's Red Army Faction and Belgium's
Communist Fighting Cells.
   The group was largely rendered ineffective when the four were
arrested at a farm south of Paris and all their documents were
confiscated. Among them was the original draft of a statement
claiming responsibility for Besse's assassination. Police also found
weapons allegedly used in the killing and a piece of the black suit
Besse was wearing when he died.
   The auto executive was killed near his home in southern Paris as
he returned from work.
   Direct Action pamphlets were found in a nearby subway station,
but the group did not formally claim responsibility for the murder
until Feb. 11, nearly three months later.
   Besse's widow, Francoise, and their five children attended the
week's hearings.
   ``The most important thing for me is that this trial took place,
and with dignity,'' she said, refusing to comment on the verdicts.
</TEXT>
