<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Africans     01-14 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Africans,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Africans Released, Heading To Beijing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two African students were released Saturday after
spending two weeks in prison for allegedly participating in a fight
with Chinese that sparked racial unrest in four cities.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Dossoumou Boni Lodovic of
Benin and Alpha Robinson of Gambia were freed one day before their
15-day sentence was to end. It said Robinson thanked his prison
guards.
   A Congolese student at Hehai University in Nanking said the two
men had gone to Beijing and had been given until Tuesday to leave
China. Their whereabouts in the capital were not immediately known.
   The student, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said most of
Nanking's 139 African students continued to boycott classes and
wanted to leave China.
   The Xinhua report said that Alex Dzabaku Dosoo, a student from
Ghana who also was arrested in connection with the Christmas Eve
brawl, was released from jail on Jan. 10 and put under house arrest
at Hehai.
   But the Congolese student said the report was false.
   ``Dosoo is not at Hehai,'' he said. ``The men released today said
he is still in jail.''
   The Ghanian Embassy has demanded Dosoo's release and has
threatened to withdraw all of its 26 students from China. It is the
only African country to do so.
   The Xinhua report said three Chinese also have been given 15-day
sentences in connection with the brawl.
   Racial unrest erupted in China on Christmas Eve when African
students fought Chinese after doorkeepers refused to let two Chinese
women attend an African party.
   The fight touched off five days of anti-black protests in Nanking
during which angry mobs of Chinese youth threw rocks and bottles at
African student dormitories and shouted ``Down with black devils.''
   As the week wore on, the protests lost much of their racist
flavor and began turning against the Chinese government. A strong
police presence in Nanking soon quelled the marches.
   The unrest spread to Hangzhou in the east, the central industrial
city of Wuhan and Beijing.
   A 10-day class boycott by African students in Hangzhou ended on
Jan. 5. On Saturday, some of the 500 African students at the Beijing
Languages Institute remained on strike. In Wuhan, one foreign
student was injured when a Chinese youth threw a rock through his
window on Dec. 29.
   The three African students were arrested on Dec. 31 by about 400
Chinese militiamen who attacked a guest house on the outskirts of
Nanking. Most of the African students from Nanking had been forced
to the guest house on Dec. 26 by Chinese police who refused to allow
them to travel to Beijing.
   African students allege that during the arrests Chinese
paramilitary forces used electric truncheons to shock and beat the
African students. The Chinese have denied the charge.
   The Xinhua report quoted Liang Ruiju, president of Hehai
University, as saying he believed ``the foreign students in our
university are still kids.''
   ``I hope they will return to their normal school activities as
soon as possible,'' he said.
   About 1,500 Africans receive Chinese scholarships as part of
Beijing's policy to emphasize its ties to the Third World.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
