<FIRST>r a AM-People SUB a0531 01-14 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People, SUB, a0531,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS third item in AM-People with PARK CITY, Utah dateline to
UPDATE with politicians skiing Saturday, one senator suffering dislocated
soldier. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel edged out
Energy Secretary John Herrington for top honors in the Senators' Ski
Cup Saturday, but the fastest senator in the field said that's
because Cabinet members have more idle time.
   ``It just goes to show you that Cabinet members have more time to
practice their skiing than senators,'' quipped Sen. Robert Kasten,
R-Wis., who finished third in the event sponsored by Sen. Jake Garn,
R-Utah.
   The event, now in its third year, drew 17 senators and was
expected to raise more than $100,000 for Salt Lake City's Primary
Children's Medical Center, Garn said.
   There was one mishap on the 20-gate slalom course when Sen. Steve
Symms, R-Idaho, fell and dislocated a shoulder. Idaho's junior
senator returned a short time later to watch the afternoon's races
with his arm in a sling.
   ``I decided to go a little faster than I should have and I caught
a gate. But what the heck, it was for a good cause,'' he said.
   Beginning skier Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said, ``If you could
handicap my skiing like you do golf, I'd be skiing about a 120.''
   Also skiing was Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del., showing how well he has
recovered since spending seven months in intensive care following
brain surgery last year.
   Biden, an early contender in the 1988 race for the Democratic
presidential nomination, dismissed claims before the race that he
was the favorite.
   ``That's what they said about the Democratic nomination,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
