<FIRST>r a AM-PTL-Dortch     01-14 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL-Dortch,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former PTL Deputy Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former PTL president Richard Dortch has
pleaded innocent to charges that he conspired with his former boss,
Jim Bakker, to divert millions of dollars in ministry donations for
his own use.
   Dortch, Bakker's onetime top deputy at PTL, was to to appear in
federal court Tuesday, but he waived his right to attend the
arraignment in papers filed Wednesday.
   He pleaded not guilty to charges of wire fraud, mail fraud and
conspiracy. The charges carry a maximum penalty of 120 years in
prison and more than $5 million in fines.
   Dortch, 57, and Bakker, 49, were indicted Dec. 5 following a
16-month grand jury investigation into how PTL operated under
Bakker. They are accused of conspiring to raise money to support
lavish lifestyles and of diverting more than $4 million in donations.
   Bakker resigned from PTL in March 1987 in the midst of a
sex-and-money scandal. His arraignment is still scheduled for
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
