<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Racism-Police     01-14 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racism-Police,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Officers Targets Of Racism Within San Bernardino Police Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor has promised to fire
those responsible for placing racist letters in the lockers of two
black policemen threatening them with violence if they took a
promotional exam.
   The incident was revealed Friday by Police Chief Donald Burnett,
who also promised to request an FBI investigation if those
responsible don't come forward within a week.
   ``The unacceptable conduct exhibited was blatant racial bigotry
against two black officers,'' said Mayor Evlyn Wilcox. ``The person
or persons involved used threats and written language of the lowest
order.''
   Officials said an internal investigation is focusing on employees
of the police department, and Ms. Wilcox said those identified as
the letters' writers would be fired.
   The mayor also issued a public apology to the officers, who were
not identified.
   The letters, signed by a group calling itself the ``Aryan Police
Officers Association,'' threatened to harm the officers and their
families if they took an oral examination they must pass to be
considered for promotion to the rank of corporal. Both officers took
the test.
   The incident was the latest of several in which black officers in
this city of 900,000 some 55 miles east of Los Angeles have been
threatened or harassed anonymously by others in the department,
officials said.
   Several weeks ago, a black patrolman found black shoe polish
smeared in his locker, officials said. A few days after that, the
same officer found his locker sprayed with black paint. That officer
also took the promotional exam.
   The letters the other two officers received said the Aryan Police
Officers Association had infiltrated the Police Department's
five-member oral exam board and had already decided which officers
would be promoted, City Councilman Tom Minor said. Approximately 70
officers have applied for three openings.
   Councilman Michael Maudsley discounted the possibility the board
had been infiltrated, however, noting one board member is black.
</TEXT>
