<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-14 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freezing Rain Across Lower Ohio Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Freezing rain and sleet hindered motorists across the lower Ohio
Valley Saturday, while snow fell from Missouri to Illinois.
   Numerous traffic accidents were reported throughout the lower
Ohio Valley as freezing rain slickened roads. Fifteen accidents
occurred within a few minutes in Charleston, W.Va., and some roads
were closed in northeast Georgia because of slick conditions.
   Snow fell from west-central Missouri to west-central Illinois
Saturday morning. The heaviest snowfall was over south-central
Missouri, where Columbia received 4 inches.
   Elsewhere, snow continued to fall over the Cascade Mountains in
the Pacific Northwest and heavy rainfall was expected to create
flooding problems in portions of western Tennessee and south-central
Kentucky due to the already saturated ground and swollen streams
from previous rainfall.
   Three inches of snow fell on the coastal mountains of Oregon and
2 inches accumulated in western Washington.
   Rain was falling from western Tennessee to the Mississippi Gulf
Coast. Flash flood watches were posted for the western two-thirds of
Tennessee and for south-central Kentucky.
   A cold front moving across the northern Plains and central
Rockies was producing gusty winds as it passed. Snow showers were
also occurring behind this front in North Dakota, reducing
visibility to near zero across parts of north-central North Dakota.
   In Norman, Okla., snowfall totaled up to 8{ inches.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14
degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo., to 85 degrees at Fort Myers,
Fla. The low in the nation Saturday morning was 35 degrees below
zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Sunday's forecast called for rain from Alabama across the
southern and mid-Atlantic states into southern New England; a
mixture of snow, rain and freezing rain from northeast New York to
southern Maine; snow over the rest of Maine; rain along the northern
Pacific coast; snow in the northern intermountain region of the
Pacific Northwest; and strong and gusty winds in the northern
Rockies.
   High temperatures were forecast in the teens and 20s in the
central Rockies and from the northern Plains across the upper
Mississippi Valley to northern portions of the upper Great Lakes; in
the 50s and 60s along the California coast as well as from southern
California across southern Arizona and New Mexico, parts of Texas
and the lower Mississippi Valley and Alabama to the middle and
southern Atlantic coast; in the 70s over much of the Florida
Peninsula; and in the 30s and 40s through the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
