<DOCNO> AP890114-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-PLO-Britain     01-14 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Britain,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Holds First Meeting With Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HABIB FAKHRI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain made its first direct contact with
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat and discussed the formation of a Middle
East peace conference, but drew criticism on Saturday from Israel.
   William Waldegrave, Britain's deputy foreign affairs minister who
met with Arafat Friday night, also planned to meet Monday with Arab
League Secretary General Chedli Klibi, the Tunis-based organization
said Saturday.
   Waldegrave said his two-hour meeting with Arafat ``constitutes a
major development in the policies of Great Britain.''
   The talks demonstrated that the world was changing and Israel
``had to change as well or it would risk being left behind,'' said
Waldegrave, who is to visit Israel in early March.
   Arafat characterized the talks, held at the home of PLO Tunisia
representative Hakam Balaoui, as ``fruitful, constructive and
useful.''
   In London, Israeli Ambassador Yoav Biran said Saturday he
regretted what he called the ``unwarranted rush of British
politicians'' to meet Arafat and the PLO.
   ``The road towards peace in the Middle East does not lead through
the PLO,'' he said. ``Behind the PLO's `charm offensive' directed at
the West, this organization adheres to its unchanged policies by
words that are directed at Arab audiences and by continued attempts
at terrorism directed at Israel.''
   Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said on Friday that
the British were well aware of Israel's attitude toward the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Israel opposes an international peace conference on the Middle
East and refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it maintains is a
terrorist organization.
   Waldegrave and Arafat, who met with reporters after their talks,
agreed that any Arab-Israeli peace conference should be sponsored by
the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, including
the United States and the Soviet Union.
   Arafat said other participants should include ``all concerned
parties, the PLO or our provisional government, Israel, Egypt,
Syria, Lebanon and Jordan.''
   It was the first time Arafat mentioned the possibility of a
provisional government sitting at a peace conference in the name of
Palestinians since the Palestine National Council, a sort of
parliament-in-exile for the PLO, decided to establish one at a
meeting in Algiers Nov. 15.
   Asked how Britain could help bring about an international
conference, Waldegrave said he did not want to exaggerate his
country's role. But he added that London has special contacts with
the United States, other European governments and a number of Arab
states.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher gave the go-ahead for
the meeting after the Arafat's public renunciation of terrorism and
implicit recognition of Israeli's right to exist in December.
   ``The intefadeh has had an extraordinary effect on international
public opinion and on Great Britain in particular,'' Waldegrave
added, referring to more than a year of unrest by Palestinians
living under Israeli occupation in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. At
least 355 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have died in the violence.
   Britain ruled Palestine before Israel was established in 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
