<FIRST>u i AM-China-Vietnam     01-14 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Vietnam,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Official Arrives In Beijing in Secret Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese official arrived unannounced in
Beijing on Saturday for what is believed to be the first high-level
talks since 1979 between China and Vietnam on the Cambodian conflict.
   Both sides attempted to keep the visit secret, and officials
refused comment on the arrival.
   China, which arms guerrillas fighting Vietnamese troops in
Cambodia, previously said it would not begin talks unless Vietnam
moves to end its 10-year-old occupation.
   However, foreign reporters peeking through a window at Beijing's
old airport saw Chinese and Vietnamese officials greet a man
resembling Vice Foreign Minister Dinh Nho Liem.
   The man ducked into a Chinese Foreign Ministry car, which sped
away. The Vietnamese ambassador to China, Nguyen Minh Phuong, came
out the front door of the airport and followed in another car.
   Liem's name was also on the flight log of Air China Flight No.
974, which flew out of Bangkok on Saturday. Japanese journalists
reported seeing Liem at the Bangkok airport.
   The Ministry of Foreign Affairs earlier reserved a VIP room at
the Beijing International Airport for a Vietnamese guest but
canceled it on short notice, an airport employee said on condition
of anonymity.
   In a possible attempt to keep the visit secret, Chinese officials
switched the welcoming venue to the old airport, which shares
runways with the newer one.
   Earlier this week, a top Cambodian resistance official said
China, at the request of the Soviet Union, agreed to its first
high-level talks with Vietnam since late 1979.
   The deal also involved the Soviet Union opening direct talks with
Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, said Prince
Norodom Ranariddh, his son and representative in Thailand. He spoke
over resistance radio and the text was obtained Thursday.
   Thai officials also said they knew of the agreement but would
give no details.
   The Vietnamese visit follows negotiations in August between China
and the Soviet Union on the Cambodian conflict, a major stumbling
block for improving long-strained ties between Moscow and Beijing.
   Relations between the two communist giants have been undergoing a
thaw in recent months. Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
will come to China next month to pave the way for the first
Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   Ties between China and Vietnam, allies during the Vietnam War,
deteriorated when Vietnam toppled the pro-Chinese Khmer Rouge in
Cambodia in 1978. China and Vietnam fought a border war early the
next year.
   The Khmer Rouge ruled Cambodia since 1975 in a reign of terror
that left at least 1 million people dead. The group is now one of
three major groups fighting the Vietnam-backed government of
Cambodia.
   China now arms the Khmer Rouge and other rebels there. The United
States backs the two non-communist groups.
   In recent weeks, better Chinese-Vietnam relations began to seem
possible.
   On Jan. 7, China said a Vietnamese proposal to withdraw all its
troops from Cambodia by September was a step forward.
   President Heng Samrin of Cambodia says 50,000 Vietnamese troops
are in Cambodia, but Western intelligence officials and rebels put
the number much higher.
   Vietnam still insists on measures to prevent the Khmer Rouge from
returning to power. However, China has refused to exclude the Khmer
Rouge from a future Cambodian government.
</TEXT>
