<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Libya 1stLd-Writethru   01-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0587,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government: No Proof Laws Broken By Libyan-Linked Firms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts penultimate graf, `Der Spiegel...' to restore drop words;
picks up last graf: The magazine...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday acknowledged
that U.S. documents link some West German companies to an alleged
chemical warfare plant in Libya, but said there still was no proof
West German laws were broken.
   West German experts returned home from Washington after examining
U.S. documents on the Libyan plant last week.
   Government spokesman Friedhelm Ost said the U.S. information
``indicates a number of German firms as well as companies from
several nations made deliveries for the Libyan chemical plant,'' but
officials found no evidence to warrant prosecution.
   Washington contends it has proof that the new Libyan plant at
Rabta is a chemical weapons factory. Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi
maintains the plant manufactures pharmaceuticals.
   ``A preliminary evaluation of the documents provided by the
Americans shows that the material is nothing beyond what we already
know about so far and would not stand up in court,'' Ost said in a
statement. He did not identify the firms named in the documents.
   Government officials previously said even with indications of
involvement in the Libyan plant, proof would still be needed that
West German companies broke their country's export laws.
   West German authorities have launched investigations into two
companies that allegedly were involved in the Libyan project:
Imhausen-Chemie of Lahr and the now-defunct I.B.I. Engineering of
Frankfurt.
   Ost said Saturday that after examining confiscated I.B.I. company
documents, authorities have not yet found hard evidence the company
broke any laws.
   West German officials at first cleared the two companies but
later said they ``cannot exclude'' that German companies may have
been involved in the Libyan project.
   Alleged participation by German firms in the Libyan plant has
embarrassed the government and resulted in strained ties with the
United States. When the accusations first came to light through
American newspapers, German leaders complained about a U.S. ``media
campaign'' against their country.
   The news magazine Der Spiegel on Saturday reported that West
German officials began receiving intelligence information about
German complicity in the plant in 1986, and not last fall as
government authorities have maintained.
   The magazine said ``several times the (West German) Federal
Intelligence Service `urgently' and `concretely' pointed to
participation by German firms.
   ``The federal government did not take reports by the German and
American secret services seriously,'' said Spiegel, which did not
identify its sources.
   But Ost said the government followed up on all information
supplied to it by its intelligence forces without delay.
   A leading federal lawmaker for the Free Democrats, junior
partners in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's coalition government, on
Saturday called for a parliamentary investigation into the
government's handling of the Libyan chemical plant affair.
   ``The scandal is growing every day' and ``damages the image of
the Federal Republic,'' Hildegart Hamm-Bruecher told Saarlandischer
Rundfunk radio in an interview.
   Der Spiegel also said the magazine has information that West
German engineers are assisting Libya in improving and rebuilding
military aircraft.
   The magazine said the engineers worked for CTTL of Liechtenstein,
a sister company of the Bavarian firm Intec.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
