<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Perez     01-14 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Perez,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush Hard to Typecast, Future Press Secretary Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto WX15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush's press secretary-designate said
Saturday she expects the American people to be ``delighted and
surprised'' by her boss' handling of her role as first lady.
   Anna Maria Perez, whose appointment was announced Saturday by
President-elect Bush's transition team, said her only real
acquaintance with Mrs. Bush was an extensive interview in early
December.
   ``Mrs. Bush is so difficult to categorize or label or typecast, I
think that I along with most of the rest of the American people are
going to be delighted and surprised by what she does with this
position,'' Perez said.
   Perez has been press secretary to Rep. John Miller, R-Wash., for
the past four years and previously worked four years for Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash.
   Perez said she plans to go into her job with ``an open mind and
the expectation that it's going to be an awful lot of hard work, but
that I'm going to really enjoy serving this administration and
working for Mrs. Bush.''
   Mrs. Bush has been interested in promoting literacy, but Perez
said she did not know yet whether the future first lady planned to
choose that or something else as a special project.
   ``We're just going to have to wait and see for a while,'' Perez
said. ``She really wants to be a wife and mother, I think.
   ``Mrs. Bush always puts her husband first, absolutely,'' Perez
said.
   Perez said she has a lot to learn about her job, adding, ``I'm
really going to be looking and learning and listening a lot in the
beginning.''
   ``My knowledge of Mrs. Bush is limited, incredibly limited _
firsthand nowledge,'' Perez said. ``I've read as much as I can about
her.''
   Perez, 37, is a native of New York City, where she attended
Hunter College. She owned a community newspaper in Washington state
before going to work for Gorton in the Senate in 1981.
   Mrs. Bush had said she wanted a black or Hispanic as her press
aide, and Perez is black.
   ``The kind of first lady she's going to be is going to evolve,''
Perez said. ``I'm going to be darn glad to go wherever she leads.''
</TEXT>
