<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strike     01-14 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strike,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Textile Workers Threaten Strike Over Pay Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at two textile factories in central
Poland threatened to go on strike Monday if management fails to meet
demands for higher pay, a regional Solidarity leader said Saturday.
   Local Solidarity committees support the wage demands. But the
strike call has upset the Solidarity regional executive committee
that backs union leader Lech Walesa's position that it is now time
to focus on reviving the banned union.
   ``We are not happy with those strikes. It looks like a
provocation or perhaps a safety valve that releases some pressure
from the boiling pot,'' said Ryszard Kostrzewa of the executive
committee for the Lodz region where the factories are located.
   The threat of further strikes comes on the eve of a Communist
Party plenum scheduled to begin Monday.
   A government source insisting on anonymity has said communist
leaders are prepared to offer to legalize Solidarity if the union
agrees to respect a law limiting wildcat strikes, enter into talks
and help the government draft political reforms.
   Walesa said Saturday he could not confirm the report that
communist leaders are preparing to offer to legalize Solidarity, but
he called such recognition ``simply the obvious solution.
   ``The needs of society are so obvious and there are so many
important problems,'' he said.
   Solidarity was outlawed in 1982 following imposition of martial
law in Poland, and has been struggling for legalization ever since.
   In recent months, there have been clear signs of increasing
tolerance of the union and Walesa, with the government hoping to win
the help of the opposition as it attempts to revitalize the economy
and reform the political system.
   Solidarity officials say workers at the Emfor factory in Lodz,
about 82 miles southwest of Warsaw, are demanding a pay raise of 32
cents an hour.
   In nearby Pabianice, workers at the Technical Fabrics Factory
want raises to compensate for losses of up to $10 a month workers
say resulted from new wage regulations introduced in the factory
four months ago, the union said.
   Lodz, the center of Poland's textile industry and one of the
country's most polluted cities, was the scene of reported work
stoppages Wednesday and Thursday when workers at Morfeo factory
outside the city demanded a pay raise of 50 percent.
   Management offered a pay increase of 20 percent Friday, but the
strike did not continue, Kostrzewa said. The workers also called on
management to improve working conditions and legalize Solidarity in
their list of 11 demands.
   In another development, an opposition spokeswoman said police
used batons and dogs Friday to break up a demonstration of about 300
people demanding the legalization of Solidarity in the southwestern
city Walbrzych.
   Maria Pinior, a spokeswoman connected to both Solidarity and the
banned Polish Socialist Party in nearby Wroclaw, said about 50
people were arrested.
</TEXT>
