<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 2000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PilotsArrested     01-14 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilots Arrested,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Arrested in Alleged Arms Smuggling to El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two pilots of a Salvadoran airliner were
arrested Saturday for allegedly trying to smuggle eight guns to El
Salvador in their luggage, said a U.S. Customs official.
   The guns were found in suitcases being taken out of a Los Angeles
International Airport terminal by two Taca International Airlines
flight attendants during a 12:30 a.m. search of the flight's
luggage, said Ed Adamson, who heads the local customs office.
   The bags held seven automatic handguns and a 12-gauge
semiautomatic shotgun nicknamed the ``street-sweeper,'' Adamson said.
   The Boeing 737 was detained but the passengers were able to leave
aboard another flight, said Adamson.
   The plane's captain, Francisco Jerez, 30, and the co-pilot,
Francisco Panameno, 29, both of El Salvador, were arrested for
investigation of violating the Neutrality Act and scheduled for
arraignment Tuesday. The act forbids the exportation of firearms
without State Department approval.
   Investigators had not determined for what purpose the guns were
intended, Adamson said.
   The airliner was held at the airport while U.S. authorities
considered whether to seize it. But the airline was cooperating and
did not appear to be connected to the alleged smuggling, said
Adamson.
   ``We're not at liberty to make any comment about it,'' said a man
at Taca's Los Angeles office who did not identify himself and
referred calls to a regional manager in New Orleans. A reservations
agent there said the regional office was closed until Sunday morning.
   The search for the guns was prompted by a tip received by agents
on Friday that the flight crew would attempt to smuggle firearms,
Adamson said.
   Agents conducted an intense search of baggage and people but
could not locate the pilots' bags, he said.
   A short time later an agent spotted two Taca flight attendants
leaving the terminal with bags with the pilots' names on them.
   The flight attendants said they had been instructed by the pilot
to take the suitcases to his hotel, and agents believe they did not
know what they held, Adamson said.
</TEXT>
