<FIRST>u a AM-SkinheadSummit 1stLd-Writethru a0550 01-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skinhead Summit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0550,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinheads Meet To Combat Racism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf with 5 grafs to UPDATE with new estimate of crowd,
quotes and other information from meeting. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `The
past year...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of Midwestern skinheads converged here
Saturday for a weekend of meetings, marches and partying, all with
the goal of fighting the racism and violence espoused by rival
skinhead groups.
   ``We want to unite all the anti-racist skinheads,'' said Brandon
Sanford of the Minneapolis Baldies, an intense 18-year-old who has
``SKINHEAD'' tattooed across the back of his shorn head.
   ``We're here to talk about what real skinheads are all about,''
he said. ``We don't want the racist people to use the skinhead image
as a recruiting tool.''
   Youths from Chicago, Milwaukee, Kansas, Nebraska and Ohio, most
in the skinhead uniform of shaved heads, tattoos, boots and flight
jackets, traveled to Minneapolis over the weekend, meeting on street
corners and fast food restaurants in the city's Uptown section.
   The talk was of music, old friendships and their fight against
the racist skinheads in their areas.
   ``We're trying to organize so people know that being a skinhead
is not about hating people,'' said Brian Lauer, a member of Brew
City Skins, a Milwaukee group that formed to counter a group of
racist skinheads in that city.
   Lauer was among some 100 skinheads attending a strategy session
at a local library Saturday. There were plans for a Sunday march
with other groups and a concert featuring local skinhead bands
Sunday night.
   At Saturday's meeting, skinheads from eight cities told of their
``crews,'' or groups, and their fight against white power skinheads
in their area.
   ``There's only one kind of skinhead, and there's bald Nazis,''
said Dave, a skinhead from Des Moines, Iowa.
   The group agreed to form a network to trade information and to
offer assistance to individual groups in various locations who are
fighting racist skinheads, the Ku Klux Klan and Nazis.
   ``We have to work together to make them (the racist skinheads)
disappear,'' said Corky, a black skinhead from Chicago.
   The past year has been filled with headlines of the violent,
racist and anti-Semitic actions of some skinhead groups around the
country.
   An Ethiopian immigrant was killed in November by skinheads
wielding baseball bats in Portland, Ore. Synagogues have been
desecrated in Dallas, Chicago and San Diego. Skinheads were involved
in a televised melee with blacks on the Geraldo Rivera show.
   These skinheads spout a philosophy of white separatism and
fascism. They talk of creating a white nation, wear Nazi swastikas
and complain of a government controlled by ``Zionists.''
   But in many cities they are opposed, often in street brawls, by
other skinheads who say their racist activities are a perversion of
the original philosophies of the skinhead movement, started by
English working class youth who listened to Ska, a racially mixed
music, and whose ranks included blacks.
   ``Being a skinhead means being hard working, being for yourself,
having a pride in your country and pride in yourself. It doesn't
matter what your color is,'' said Eli Simbura, an 18-year-old member
of the Baldies whose cramped apartment served as a rallying place
for the skinheads attending the weekend activities.
   The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith claims there may be as
many as 2,000 racist skinheads in 21 states, and a check in several
cities shows at least as many anti-racist skinheads. But an accurate
estimate is difficult because skinheads often move from city to city.
   Skinheads pride themselves in being violent in support of their
ideas and their friendships. The Baldies, whose 40 to 50 members
include blacks, Hispanics and Orientals, have warred with the White
Knights, a smaller group of local racist skinheads.
   ``We are violent,'' Simbura said proudly. ``We believe in direct
action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
