<FIRST>u p AM-IndianaRace 1stLd-Writethru a0560 01-14 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indiana Race, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0560,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats, Republicans Choose Candidates for 4th District Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with results of Republican voting, quotes from
winner.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic loser in November's 4th
District congressional race and a Republican mayoral aide were
nominated Saturday to run in a special election to succeed the man
filling Dan Quayle's Senate seat.
   Republicans took seven ballots to nominate Fort Wayne public
safety director Dan Heath for his party's nomination. Heath, who
also serves an as aide to Mayor Paul Helmke, defeated eight
candidates in voting by GOP precinct committee leaders.
   Democratic Party leaders in the district selected Jill Long, a
former council member in Valparaiso, by acclamation. In 1986, Long
lost the U.S. Senate race to Quayle.
   The 4th District seat, one of Indiana's 10 House seats, has been
vacant since GOP incumbent Dan Coats resigned after then-Gov. Robert
Orr selected him to replace Vice President-elect Quayle as Indiana's
junior senator.
   Coats was sworn in to his Senate seat Jan. 3. Quayle will take
the oath of office with President-elect Bush on Jan. 20.
   The special election is scheduled for March 28.
   The hopefuls for the GOP nomination included three state
representatives: Brad Fox of Rome City, Mitchell V. Harper of Fort
Wayne and Phyllis J. Pond of New Haven. Other active candidates
besides Heath were William Cummings of Fort Wayne, a retired Air
Force officer; Michael Loomis, a Marion County deputy prosecutor;
Jeff Turner, an Auburn lawyer who survived until the final ballot;
and George B. Witwer, co-owner of the Bluffton News-Banner.
   A ninth person, John A. Caldemone of Fort Wayne, declared his
candidacy but did not campaign actively.
   ``I really enjoyed this campaign,'' Heath said after his victory.
   ``We need to get together and make sure we take a united front to
Jill Long,'' he said. ``We are a united party.''
   Long, who unsuccessfully challenged Coats' bid last fall for a
fifth term, was the only announced candidate for the Democratic spot
on the ballot.
   Coats, a former Quayle aide when Quayle held the seat for two
terms in the late 1970s, won the seat in 1980 when Quayle made his
successful bid for the Senate.
</TEXT>
