<HEAD>Bomb Explodes in West Belfast, Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RESTORES day in 1st graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs exploded 45 minutes apart
in Belfast and Londonderry on Saturday night, injuring at least two
soldiers and two civilians, police said.
   In the first attack, a soldier and two civilians were hurt when a
bomb exploded near Dunmisk Park in a residential section of Roman
Catholic west Belfast, a police spokesman said.
   One woman was treated for shock at a hospital and released, and a
man and the soldier were receiving treatment but their injuries also
were not believed to be serious, said the police officer, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   The area was cordoned off after the explosion just before 11 p.m.
(6 p.m. EST), which occurred while an army patrol was in the area,
he said. He said earlier police statements that a second device had
been found in the vicinity could not be confirmed.
   The spokesman said one soldier was injured slightly in the bomb
explosion in Londonderry, 65 miles northeast of Belfast, at about
11:45 p.m. in the city's central business district.
   It also exploded when an army patrol had been in the area.
   There were no claims of responsibility for the attacks, but the
army has been targeted by the outlawed Irish Republican Army in its
fight to oust Britain from the province.
