<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Whales     01-14 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Whales,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gray Whales Saved In Baja California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of rescuers fought against time and
managed to free 31 gray whales that were beached near the southern
tip of the Baja California peninsula, officials said Saturday.
   Tourists from the United States, Canada and other countries
teamed up with college students, fishermen and Mexican navy
personnel to free the whales late Friday from the Bay of La Paz,
said Blas Castro, an official with the federal Fisheries Department.
   The whales ran aground Friday morning in the knee-deep waters of
the bay ``after a change in the currents caused by winds caused them
to lose their direction,'' Castro said.
   Students from the Center for Biological Studies of Baja
California Sur, joined by the other rescuers ``pulled with their
arms and used small boats to nudge and free the whales,'' said
Daniel Roldan, editor of the La Paz newspaper La Extra.
   ``It was a beautiful thing, a wonderful effort,'' Roldan said.
   ``The whales went back to deeper waters in the Gulf and it
appears they're out of danger,'' Castro said.
   Those that beached themselves Friday measured between 10 and 30
feet long and weighed an average four tons, the Excelsior news
agency reported.
   The gray whales migrate to the same lagoons off Baja California's
Pacific coast each year from their feeding grounds off Alaska. The
lagoons become mammoth nurseries for the gray whales from January to
March each year.
</TEXT>
