<FIRST>u a AM-ExplosivesSeized 1stLd-Writethru a0530 01-14 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Explosives Seized, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plastic Explosives Seized, Five Arrested In Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8th graf, `The federal' with two grafs to UPDATE with comment
from sheriff's sergeant about lack of suspicion of terrorist involvement.
Picks up 9th graf, `We're real...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 pounds of a powerful plastic
explosive that had been stolen from a mine was seized in a raid by
agents who posed as would-be buyers for the material, authorities
said.
   Five people were arrested in the raid on a motel Friday night
where agents had rented rooms to arrange the bogus purchase,
authorities said.
   There was enough explosive, known as C-3 or Tovex, to blow up a
three-block area, said police in this community of 50,000 about 45
miles north of Denver.
   Following the arrests, authorities went to the Fort Collins home
of one of the suspects, where they seized armor-piercing rifle
rounds, thousands of rounds of ammunition, an AK-47 rifle,
hollow-point revolver rounds and homemade bullets designed to pierce
bullet-proof vests worn by police, police said.
   Agents also confiscated a number of handguns; switchblade knives;
military flak jackets; a scope-mounted AR-15, described as a
civilian version of the military M-16 rifle; 2,000 blasting caps;
and a large amount of detonation cord.
   Books and magazines about terrorism and survival tactics also
were found, said Longmont police Sgt. Carl McIntyre.
   FBI spokesman Dick Schussler refused to comment Saturday on the
group's possible motive.
   Boulder County Sheriff's Sgt. George Dunphy said there had been
no hint from any of the investigators that suspected terrorists were
involved. Dunphy said the investigation had been suspended for the
weekend and the five suspects remained in the county jail.
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, which
participated in the monthlong undercover investigation along with
the sheriff's department, is in charge of the case, Dunphy said. ATF
agents could not be reached for comment Saturday.
   ``We're real pleased with how this thing went down,'' Sheriff
Brad Leach said.
   He identified those arrested for investigation of possession and
sale of explosives as: Jon Alexander Kobert, 29, Richard Sanford
Baxter, 51, and Andrew Wallace Ferguson, 29, all of Fort Collins;
Jeffery Bart Rudolph, 29, of Akron, Colo.; and Evelyn Jean
Moschetti, 18, of Laporte.
   It was at Rudolph's rented home in Fort Collins that officers
found the cache of weapons and ammunition.
   Authorities stalked out the motel after an undercover agent
completed a deal to buy more than 300 pounds of the powerful
explosive for $10,000 cash. The explosives were stolen from a mine
in Left Hand Canyon northwest of Boulder in September, Leach said.
   ``This is a lot of explosives to be floating around,'' Leach
said. ``To get over 300-plus pounds of this stuff off the street is
a good thing.''
   Leach said the investigation began when local and federal
authorities received information about suspects in the mine theft.
Negotiations were conducted with Kobert to buy large amounts of
explosives, complete with blasting caps and detonation cord.
   All five suspects were being held in Boulder County Jail.
</TEXT>
