<FIRST>r i AM-BaghdadSheraton     01-14 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baghdad Sheraton,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baghdad Sheraton Goes On The Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday offered one of
its major hotels, the Baghdad Sheraton, for sale to the private
sector.
   State-run newspapers carried an advertisement offering the
307-room hotel to a private company with at least $150 million in
capital. The hotel is wholly owned by the government and run by the
international Sheraton chain.
   The ruling Revolutionary Command Council in September abolished
the state tourism authority and decided to sell all of its assets,
including five major hotels in Baghdad.
   The move to sell tourist facilities is a part of President Saddam
Hussein's drive to develop the private sector in what has been a
staunch socialist economy.
   Selling state assets is seen as a means of overcoming massive
government debts and stimulating the economy battered by the
8-year-old war with Iran that ended with a cease-fire in August.
   The Sheraton chain runs another hotel in Iraq's southern port of
Basra that was badly damaged by Iranian shelling.
   Sheraton officials said they have no idea whether it was also up
for sale, but they confirmed the government has announced it would
be on the market soon.
</TEXT>
