<FIRST>u a AM-BridgeOut 1stLd-Writethru a0583 01-14 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Out, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barge Knocks Three-Mile Bridge Out Of Commission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with bridge to be closed for three
weeks, picks up 4th graf, pvs, `Construction workers...'; deletes outdated
10th graf pvs, `There was no ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge slammed into a concrete pillar
supporting the center of the three-mile Pensacola Bay Bridge on
Saturday, knocking the pillar into the water and halting vehicle and
marine traffic, officials said.
   The four-lane bridge was clear of traffic at the time and no
injuries were reported.
   The bridge is the only direct link between Pensacola and suburban
Gulf Breeze and is used daily by thousands of commuters. The only
other land access is a detour of about 60 miles.
   The bridge will remain closed to all boat and vehicular traffic
for three weeks while the southbound lanes are stabilized, said Paul
Hazucha, regional maintenance engineer for the Florida Department of
Transportation.
   Two-lane traffic then will be permitted in the northbound lanes
while permanent repairs are made, which will take from four to six
months, Hazucha said.
   Construction workers building an emergency lane on the bridge
``saw the situation coming and cleared the site so there were no
cars actually traveling over that spot,'' said Gulf Breeze City
Manager Jack Tuttle. ``Fortunately, obviously, there were no
vehicles that went into the water.''
   Officials said it was not immediately known why the barge was
unable to navigate away from the pillar.
   Junius Boling, of Mary Esther, said he was fishing on the end of
the Gulf Breeze pier next to the bridge Saturday morning when the
barge hit about 100 feet away.
   ``I just stood here and watched him take out the end of the
bridge,'' Boling said. ``They scared the fish away.''
   Initial reports indicated the southbound side of the U.S. 98
bridge was sagging about five feet, said Coast Guard Lt. Mark Kasper
in New Orleans.
   A 32-foot Coast Guard patrol boat was on the scene, and a bridge
inspection team from the state Department of Transportation was
assigned to assess the damage, he said.
   The barge was operated by Hollywood Marine Co. of Houston and was
empty of cargo at the time, officials said.
   The bridge is part of the main coastal highway in the Florida
Panhandle. It has been undergoing a multimillion-dollar expansion to
add emergency lanes on each side.
</TEXT>
