<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Pakistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Reports Attacking Intruding Pakistani Helicopters, Armored
Column</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 5 grafs to UPDATE with guerrilla leader saying provisional
government will be declared in a month.</HEAD>
<UNK>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan said Saturday that it attacked two
intruding Pakistani helicopters and an armored column that committed
an ``unprecedented act of aggression,'' the official Soviet news
agency Tass reported.
   Tass quoted official Afghan news agency Bakhtar as saying the
helicopters were carrying ``leaders of extremist organizations,
foreign military advisers and high-ranking Pakistani officers to the
area'' when they landed at a farm in Nangarhar province on Monday.
   Soviet and Afghan media often refer to the U.S.-backed,
anti-government guerrillas as ``extremists.''
   Tass said the Pakistani mechanized column reached the same area
on the same day, ``bringing armed people, arms and ammunition.'' The
Soviet-backed Afghan military attacked, damaging or destroying the
two helicopters and some armored cars, it said.
   The report, quoting the Afghan military command, did not give any
casualty figures. There was no immediate word from the Pakistani
government or Afghan guerrillas based in Pakistan.
   ``The Pakistani armed forces committed an unprecedented action of
aggression against the republics of Afghanistan,'' Tass quoted the
Afghan military command as saying.
   ``Islamabad's actions not only flagrantly violate the letter and
spirit of the Geneva agreements, but also enter into direct
contradiction with the universally recognized norms of international
relations,'' it said. Afghanistan made a formal protest to Pakistani
diplomats in Kabul.
   Anti-Marxist resistance fighters who oppose Kabul's pro-Soviet
government operate out of bases inside Pakistan and near the border.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union repeatedly have accused the
United States and Pakistan of violating the April 14 Geneva
agreement by continuing to supply the resistance with weapons.
   Under the agreement, the Soviet Union is to withdraw its 100,000
soldiers from Afghanistan by Feb. 15. Half of the soldiers were
withdrawn between May 15 and Aug. 15, but Soviet diplomats have said
they might not meet the final deadline because of continued
interference by Pakistan and the United States.
   In another development, guerrilla leader Sibghatullah Mojaddidi
said his alliance plans to announce a provisional government within
a month, the Saudi Arabian newspaper Okaz reported Saturday.
   Mojaddidi, spokesman for a coalition of seven Pakistan-based
Afghan guerrilla groups, said in an interview with Okaz that his
group would not object to the return of Afghanistan's deposed king,
Zahir Shah.
   The former monarch has lived in Italy since his overthrow in 1973.
   The guerrillas are demanding power be turned over to them
exclusively after the Soviet Union withdraws its remaining troops.
   But the Soviet Union, which sent troops into Afghanistan in 1979
in support of a Marxist regime, insists President Najib's government
should stay on after the military withdrawal.
</TEXT>
