<HEAD>Musical Director Fired In Dispute Over Pay, Duties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf `Several artistic...' with 1 graf to ADD first
reference to Patrice Chereau. Pickup 9th graf `Barenboim's firing...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The artistic and musical director of the new Opera
of the Bastille has been fired in a dispute over duties and salary,
and a stage director said Saturday he will refuse to direct the
opera's debut presentation.
   Daniel Barenboim, a conductor and concert pianist, was ousted
Friday after contending an agreement he signed with the former
conservative government of Jacques Chirac guaranteed his position
and a salary of more than $1 million.
   But Pierre Berge, president of the Association of Theaters of the
Paris Opera, told a news conference Friday the accord was signed
``in haste'' and was not valid.
   The May 5 accord said Barenboim should receive a salary of
between $1.1 million and $1.2 million. Berge, appointed in August,
offered Barenboim a $570,000 salary as musical director.
   Barenboim told Europe 1 radio he considered the development a
``breach of contract'' and threatened to sue.
   Berge said allowing Barenboim to be artistic and musical director
was giving him too much power.
   ``It is a little bizarre and that doesn't exist in practically
any country of the world,'' Berge said.
   Several artistic personalities, including stage director Patrice
Chereau, composer Pierre Boulez and singer Jessy Norman, signed a
message to President Francois Mitterrand and Minister of Culture
Jack Lang, saying they would not be involved in the programs
Barenboim planned unless his duties were restored.
   Barenboim's firing may throw in to question the opening date of
the Bastille Opera, set for early next year.
   On Saturday, Chereau said on FR3 television that he will not
direct the first show at the Bastille Opera because of Barenboim's
firing.
