<HEAD>Klan March Provokes Angry Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King's Church, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry crowd hurled rocks at Ku Klux Klan
members as they marched Saturday in response to the Martin Luther
King Jr. holiday, but no injuries were reported, police said.
   ``There was a large group participating and a large group
watching, despite a downpour,'' said police Lt. Bob Barnes said.
``Some of the crowd got to throwing rocks at the march.''
   There were about 400 Klan members marching and about as many
bystanders, he said. The marchers included racist skinheads, who
appeared to be the first to become embroiled the with observers,
Barnes said.
   The march had progressed only a short distance when the rock
throwing began, Barnes said, but the violence did not last long.
   The march is the fourth staged by the Klan in Pulaski since
King's birthday was declared a national holiday.The civil rights
leader was killed in April 1968 in Memphis by James Earl Ray, who is
serving a life sentence in Brushy Mountain prison in east Tennessee.
   Pulaski, 80 miles south of Nashville near the Alabama border, is
where the Klan was created after the Civil War.
