<HEAD>With AM-Mexico-Oil Workers, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A labor chief famed for his Las Vegas gambling
exploits faces an inquiry into the source of his wealth as part of
the crackdown on the leadership of the Oil Workers Union, government
sources said Saturday.
   Former Sen. Salvador Barragan Camacho already has been charged
with possession of illegal weapons. Barragan Camacho, the union's
secretary-general until last week, declared his innocence on the
weapons charges early Saturday from a bed at the Cardiological
Hospital.
   He checked into the hospital complaining of heart trouble last
week after federal officials raided the fortress-like home of his
mentor and the union's top leader, Joaquin Hernandez Galicia.
   Authorities also raided Barragan Camacho's home in Mexico City,
confiscating several high-caliber weapons, ammunition and silencers.
   A search of his $75,000, bulletproof limousine turned up more
than $1 million in jewelry, cash and bars of silver. The jewelry
included a gold bracelet that authorities said weighed almost half a
pound and several gold medals from gambling tournaments.
   The Excelsior news service said Barragan Camacho declared assets
of less than $100,000 six years ago when he began his recently
completed term in the senate.
   Barragan Camacho was the last of the 51 suspects to enter a plea
in the crackdown on the Oil Workers Union.
   Administrative judge Jose Luis Garcia on Saturday ruled that 28
of those arrested on arms charges were eligible to post bail. No top
union leaders or La Quina associates were included in the ruling.
   Government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, have
indicated more arrests are expected. The sources also said there
will be an investigation into Barragan Camacho's ``unexplained
riches.''
   The former senator was an enthusiastic patron of Las Vegas
casinos. He once reportedly gambled away more than $1 million in a
matter of minutes.
   His extravagance at the gaming tables was documented in books and
articles several years ago by the late journalist Manuel Buendia.
   The union crackdown began Tuesday with a spectacular raid by
police and soldiers on Hernandez Galicia's home in Ciudad Madero on
the Gulf Coast. A federal agent died in the shootout.
   Hernandez Galicia and other union officials face a variety of
charges, including illegal arms possession, murder and tax evasion.
   Judicial officials said Saturday that Barragan Camacho's
condition is stable and they expect him to join Hernandez Galicia
and other union leaders in prison next week.
