<FIRST>r a AM-DrugSentence     01-14 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Sentence,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>40-Year Prison Term for Mexican Drug Smuggler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former farm worker was sentenced to 40
years in prison by a judge who called him ``the general, admiral,
chief'' of a multimillion-dollar heroin and cocaine ring.
   Andres Carrasco Aragon, 34, a Mexican national who lived in
Tacoma at the time of his arrest last year, was sentenced Friday by
U.S. District Judge Jack Tanner. The sentence was the second-longest
prison term in a federal drug case in the state.
   Leonel Cortez-Vaca, 40, of Spanaway, and Maximino Tapia-Caballos,
31, of Woodbrook, also were sentenced by Tanner to four years in
prison for their part in the drug conspiracy.
   They were among 17 people, besides Carrasco, who have pleaded
guilty or been convicted of drug-related offenses in the case.
   Carrasco's wife, Rosanna Carrasco, was sentenced to six months in
jail for taking telephone messages for him in the smuggling
operation. His brother is one of two defendants who remain fugitives
in the case.
   ``You were the general, admiral, chief _ at least in this area,''
Tanner said. Carrasco was named in 42 counts of a 130-count federal
indictment, including a charge of running a continuing criminal
enterprise.
   Four days into his trial in November, he pleaded guilty to
reduced charges in exchange for a promise by government lawyers not
to recommend more than 40 years in prison.
   The charges he pleaded guilty to included possession with intent
to distribute more than 100 grams of heroin, possession with intent
to distribute more than 500 grams of cocaine, conspiracy to
distribute heroin and conspiracy to distribute cocaine.
   The law allows no parole, and even with good behavior he must
serve at least 34 years behind bars.
   Carrasco was described as a hard worker in the tomato and pepper
fields of an impoverished area of Mexico as a boy and later in the
apple orchards of north-central Washington and the tree farms around
Raymond.
   Assistant U.S. attorney Jerry Diskin said Carrasco began his drug
ring in December 1986 and expanded it until last May, when he and
the others were arrested by federal agents after a nine-month
investigation.
