<SECOND>AM-King-Calendar Foulup,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calendar Oversight Riles King Holiday Observers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-King's Church, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Calendars given to managers of 65
McDonald's restaurants mark the state holiday for Martin Luther King
Jr. as ``National Nothing Day'' because of what an advertising
agency calls its embarrassing but innocent mistake.
   The civil rights leader, who was shot to death in Memphis in
April 1968, was born Jan. 15, 1929, but his birthday is being
observed by Tennessee and most states on the third Monday in
January, which this year is Jan. 16.
   John Malmo Advertising denoted that day ``National Nothing Day''
on calendars given to managers of Memphis-area McDonald's
restaurants to remind them when sales promotions start and end.
   ``It certainly was not done intentionally or maliciously,'' said
Cathleen West of Malmo in the wake of angry comments by black
residents of Memphis. ``It was a terrible clerical oversight.''
   ``It was unfortunately a terrible, terrible oversight,'' said Ms.
West, who handles McDonald's account with Malmo. ``It's not
McDonald's fault.''
   The error was not noticed until an annoyed McDonald's employee
called to complain.
   The National Nothing Day holiday has been listed on the calendar
in past years too, she said, as a spoof of special days that salute
everything from pickles to world poetry.
   New calendars were mailed to the restaurants this week, the
agency said.
   Steve Lykins, vice president of Century Management, which owns
two dozen McDonald's restaurants in the region, said that the day
before the mistake was discovered, the company saluted 10 black high
school students as ``McDonald's Talented Teens: Black History Makers
of Tomorrow,'' handing out plaques and $200 awards at a banquet
featuring black community leaders.
</TEXT>
