<HEAD>American-Statesman Names Managing Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Lowery, city editor of the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, has been named managing editor of the Austin
American-Statesman, the editor of the Texas newspaper announced.
   Lowery, 42, will direct day-to-day newsroom operations and
supervise news-gathering and production.
   ``David Lowery brings to this job many years of experience in
managing news-gathering operations. He will provide strong
leadership to a talented staff,'' said Maggie Balough,
American-Statesman editor.
   The newspaper said he begins his new job Feb. 6.
   The American-Statesman and Journal-Constitution are owned by
Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises Inc.
   Lowery earned a bachelor of arts degree in political science from
the University of Richmond in Virginia in 1968 and spent the next
two years in the Army, including a tour of duty in South Vietnam.
   He earned a master's degree in journalism from Ohio State
University in 1971 and completed a National Endowment for the
Humanities Fellowship at Yale University in 1980.
   Lowery's newspaper career has included work at the Hollywood
(Fla.) Sun-Tattle, the Richmond (Va.) News Leader, the Cincinnati
(Ohio) Enquirer and the Seattle (Wash.) Times. He joined the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution in 1985.
   Lowery replaces Jeff Bruce, who was named executive editor of the
Longview (Texas) News-Journal.
