<HEAD>Elderly Woman Who Fatally Beat Sister With Mop Gets Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 85-year-old woman who beat her
older sister to death with a mop received three years probation
Friday and was ordered to remain at her retirement home under
virtual house arrest.
   Edna Lamont was convicted of involuntary manslaughter in the
March 12 bludgeoning death of Mary McBride, 86.
   Ms. Lamont told authorities the victim suffered from Alzheimer's
disease, a degenerative ailment that robs the elderly of their
mental faculties.
   Deputy District Attorney T.K. Herman called the sentence
appropriate.
   ``There was strong evidence that (Lamont) was suffering from the
same kind of mental dementia that the deceased suffered,'' Herman
said.
   Ms. Lamont wasn't present at her sentencing because of
deteriorating health, he said, adding that she had blocked the
slaying from her mind.
   Superior Court Judge Robert Thomas convicted Ms. Lamont of
involuntary manslaughter, based on preliminary hearing transcripts,
after a Municipal Court judge changed a murder charge to the lesser
offense.
   Ms. Lamont was ordered not to leave her retirement home without a
judge's approval, and only then when supervised by a probation
officer.
</TEXT>
