<DOCNO> AP890114-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv14-15   01-14 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 14-15,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Experts Predicting Record-level Volume For 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Throughout the country, aging bridges crack or
sway as traffic clogs pot-hole-ridden roads and highways. Public
dams and sewers cry out for more than a good plumbing job.
   Then there's the problem of trashing our trash...
   As the nation's infrastructure and public works systems show
increasing signs of deterioration, many public officials are
expected to turn more and more to bonds. At least that's what
experts predicted this past week at a forum by Municipal Bond
Investors Assurance Corp., a leading insurer of municipal bonds.
   ``There's no way of escaping those needs. You've got to get to
work,'' said forum participant Austin V. Koenen, managing director
for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``I'm very bullish on volume.''
   An MBIA survey of municipal bond professionals predicted that
volume of tax-exempt municipal bonds _ most often used to finance
infrastructure and other public projects _ will rise 7 percent in
1989 to a record level $120 billion.
   Volume for the taxable municipal market should reach $2.8 billion
this year, compared with an estimated $2.2 billion in 1988, it said.
   The survey suggested the biggest increase would come in bond
issues for transportation, estimating a 61 percent rise in volume
over last year to $14.08 billion. However, the biggest chunk of
newly issued bonds, an estimated $30.04 billion this year vs. $28.38
billion in 1988, will be used to refund old debt, the survey said.
   It predicted a 58 percent rise for gas and electric to $12.14
billion; a 48 percent rise for water and sewer projects to $12.67
billion; a 35 percent rise for hospitals to $14.94 billion; a 26
percent rise for education to $20.31 billion; and just a fractional
rise in housing to $13.96 billion.
   In last year's general election alone voters nationwide approved
a record $13.8 billion in state and local bond issues to finance
projects ranging from road and bridge repairs to new prison
facilities.
   Experts say the anticipated increase in bond volume is largely
due to a steady reduction of federal assistance and the historical
neglect of public works projects by some local and state governments.
   ``Until very recently ... the need to replenish and expand public
works has been largely ignored,'' John E. Petersen, senior director
of the Government Finance Research Center, noted in a separate
report on infrastructure needs and financing released at the forum.
   ``By the early 1980s, the infrastructure was wearing out faster
than it was being replaced,'' he said.
   Last year, one of the nation's busiest bridges _ the
Williamsburg, which links Manhattan and Brooklyn _ was shut down for
more than three months after inspectors discovered extensive
corrosion. The bridge was built in 1903 for bicycles and horse-drawn
buggies. When closed it was carrying more than 100,000 vehicles and
420 trains daily.
   Koenen noted that just a few weeks ago, the 122-year-old Roebling
Suspension Bridge, which spans the Ohio River in Cincinnati, was
closed briefly after it began swaying under heavy pedestrian traffic
following the Bengals-Seahawks football game. But officials later
declared the bridge safe.
   Supporting the MBIA survey on projected volume, Petersen's study
found that capital investment needs are by far the greatest in the
areas of highways, streets and bridges. Next to that comes public
transit, water supply and distribution, waste water treatment, solid
waste disposal and airports.
   Petersen also noted that changing population patterns will affect
municipal bond issuance.
   ``If the population trend continues, 62 percent of the population
will live in the South and West by 2010, compared with 48 percent in
the 1970s,'' he said. ``That's going to stimulate spending needs.''
   Another factor that could effect future municipal spending is the
so-called ``Greenhouse Effect,'' or the pollution-caused warming of
the atmosphere, Petersen said.
   ``Recent studies indicate that global warming, with the resulting
rise in water levels due to polar melting, will affect economic
activity and infrastructure spending in coastal areas.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890114-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0510EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv14-15   01-14 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 14-15,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>1988 Futures Volume Set New Record; Drought Boosted Ag Markets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading volume on the nation's futures exchanges rose by a modest
7.3 percent last year as a drought-driven surge in agricultural
hedging and speculation helped offset a slump in the stock-index
futures markets.
   Volume on the 11 U.S. futures exchanges totaled a record 295
million contracts, compared with 275 million contracts traded in
1987, according to figures compiled by the Futures Industry
Association, a trade group.
   The increase compares with volume expansion of nearly 25 percent
in 1987 and continues a growth pattern of more than two decades.
   On futures exchanges, people trade contracts for future
deliveries of commodities _ such as grain, cattle, gold and crude
oil _ and financial instruments, including government securities,
stocks and foreign currencies.
   Commercial players _ those directly involved in producing, buying
or selling a particular commodity or financial instrument _ use
futures to hedge against losses in their business dealings or
financial investments. Speculators are investors who seek to profit
from the fluctuating prices of the contracts.
   Agricultural futures trading in the United States dates back more
than 120 years but financial futures, introduced in the early 1970s,
now account for most trades.
   Last year, financial futures trading accounted for 139.1 million,
or nearly 57 percent, of the total futures volume, FIA figures show.
   More than half of those trades involved the Chicago Board of
Trade's U.S. Treasury bond contract, with a volume of 70.3 million,
a 5.2 percent increase over the previous year.
   The Chicago Board of Trade, the oldest and largest U.S. futures
exchange, also reported a dramatic resurgence in grain and soybean
futures trading. Wheat volume soared by 75 percent, soybean trading
jumped 69 percent, and corn volume surged 53 percent as the worst
drought in 50 years withered crops and sent prices skyrocketing.
   ``The drought of 1988 added significant increases to volume in
agricultural trading,'' said Karsten Mahlmann, the exchange's
chairman. He said the exchange's more lightly traded agricultural
options, hedging instruments that are similar to futures, also
``worked extremely well to manage risk in the agricultural markets.''
   Overall volume at the Chicago Board of Trade grew by 12.5 percent
in 1988, the 20th consecutive year of record volume for the
exchange. With a total of 143.1 million futures and options
contracts traded, the Chicago Board of Trade's share of the industry
was 48.5 percent.
   The nation's second-largest futures exchange, the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, did not fare as well. Officials reported a 7.5
percent decrease in volume, mainly due to a 40 percent drop in
stock-index futures trading at the exchange.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange trades the Standard &amp; Poor's 500
stock-index futures contract, by far the industry's leading contract
of its type despite the drop in volume. Officials blamed the decline
on slack interest in stock market investing following the crash of
October 1987.
   But the Chicago Mercantile Exchange also reported a 6.6 percent
increase in foreign currency futures trading, including a 6.3
percent gain in its Eurodollar futures contract _ the exchange's
volume leader _ and a 20 percent leap in yen futures.
   Overall volume at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange last year
totaled 78 million contracts, giving the exchange a 26.4 percent
share of the industry.
   The New York Mercantile Exchange, home of crude-oil and platinum
futures, scored a 33.5 percent volume increase with 34.3 million
contracts traded. The volume placed the exchange third in the
industry with an 11.6 percent share.
   New York's Commodity Exchange, which specializes in gold, silver
and copper, saw its volume shrink by 10 percent to 19.2 million for
a 6.5 percent share of the industry.
   New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange traded a record 10
million contracts, up from 6.3 million in 1988, for a 3.4 percent
share.
   Trading volume at Chicago's MidAmerica Commodity Exchange reached
a record 3.4 million contracts, a 44 gain over 1987, giving the
exchange a 1.2 percent share of the industry.
   The New York Cotton Exchange reported a record turnover of 3.1
million cotton, orange-juice and financial futures contracts, a 19
percent gain, for a 1 percent share of the industry.
   The remaining 1.4 percent of the industry volume was divided
among the New York Futures Exchange, the Kansas City Board of Trade,
the Minneapolis Grain Exchange and the Chicago Rice &amp; Cotton
Exchange.
   These figures do not include statistics from the Chicago Board
Options Exchange, which trades only financial options.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890114-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv14-15   01-14 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 14-15,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stocks Defy Rising Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are uneasy times for stock market investors
who key their strategies to the ups and downs of interest rates.
   For the past several weeks, interest rates have been rising,
especially in the short-term money markets.
   That's supposed to spell trouble for stocks, by acting as a drag
on the economy and by luring investors' money away from the stock
market and into interest-bearing securities such as Treasury bills.
   But things haven't worked out that way of late. The stock market
has rallied since mid-November, recently reaching a series of new
highs since the October 1987 crash.
   A lot of money managers at investing institutions who have been
shying away from stocks are now faced with the possibility that a
train might be leaving the station without them.
   A substantial corps of skeptics on Wall Street remains
unimpressed by the market's recent strength.
   Some of these observers say it is merely a temporary
manifestation of the ``January effect,'' a much-documented tendency
of stock prices to rise in the early stages of a new year.
   In simplest terms, the January effect is believed to arise from
several seasonal factors _ including the cessation of yearend
selling for tax purposes, and infusions of new money into pension
plans.
   If this is the only driving force for the market's advance, the
rally is presumably in for a limited run.
   A good many analysts, however, contend that the rise in stock
prices is also the product of an abundance of fear and pessimism
that still persists.
   Market rallies typically begin in periods of gloom, and end when
all the doubters have been converted to optimistic views and
expended all their reserve buying power.
   ``Conservative attitudes of individuals, 10 percent cash reserves
in mutual funds and similar high cash positions of pension accounts
are the best sources of support for the stock market,'' said Rao
Chalasani at Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben Inc.
   ``The U.S. continues to be a place of value for foreign
investors. Those dynamics will support the stock market as long as
earnings hold up.''
   In the past week, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose
31.78 to 2,226.07.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index gained 1.62 to
159.58; the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
climbed 2.35 to 387.09, and the American Stock Exchange market value
index was up 4.53 at 315.93.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 153.57 million shares a day,
against 153.39 million in the first week of 1989.
   Analysts who take a bullish view say there is another possible
explanation for the recent gains in stock prices.
   It could be, they suggest, that interest rates will soon stop
rising and turn downward.
   ``The so-called upward pressure on interest rates may prove to be
illusory,'' said William LeFevre at Advest Inc.
   Utility stocks, highly sensitive to changes in interest-rate
expectations, have lately traded well above their low points of last
year, he points out.
   The behavior of the Dow Jones utility average ``says interest
rates are headed lower, not higher'' in the intermediate to
long-term future, LeFevre maintains.
   Talk has even begun to stir on the Street of an increasingly
powerful rise in stock and bond prices should the economy slow and
the Federal Reserve relax its recent credit-tightening.
   ``When that occurs, all will know that short rates are due to
peak and the proper place for assets is in long bonds and stocks,''
said John Connolly at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``We could see a
scramble develop sometime soon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Jan. 14-15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
