<DOCNO> AP890114-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-14-89 0451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-OilPrices     01-14 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indications that world oil production is
declining helped strengthen some crude oil prices this week.
   OPEC Secretary General Subroto said Friday the cartel's output
for January could fall below the 18.5 million barrel-a-day target.
   In addition, ongoing problems in the North Sea have reduced oil
production by about 500,000 barrels a day.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 31
cents to close at $18.48 a barrel Friday after advancing 3 cents on
Thursday. The contract traded as high as $18.64 but retreated on
profit-taking, analysts said. Other contract months were mixed.
   However, traders noted that prices of crude contracts between
June and November fell. OPEC's accord took effect Jan. 1 and extends
for six months. Many economists speculate that OPEC will raise its
volume in the second half of the year.
   WTI was trading in the $15 range when members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed in November to cut back
production to 18.5 million barrels. Traders say prices have risen
amid signs OPEC is abiding by the agreement and new speculation on
Friday encouraged further buying.
   ``A statement from Subroto that January production would be below
the quota was probably the main factor moving the market,'' William
Byers, an analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said Friday
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
futures rose. The February contract for gasoline closed 0.70 cent
higher at 49.97 cents a gallon.
   Heating oil futures ended the day mixed, with the February
contract up 0.11 cent at 52.95 cents a gallon. The March contract
also rose, but subsequent months declined.
   Heating oil prices have not firmed along with other energy prices
recently as demand has fallen off due to seasonal factors, traders
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
